# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: signal-transduction
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] In biology, signals are mostly chemical in nature, but can also be physical cues such as pressure, voltage, temperature, or light.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Chemical signals are molecules with the ability to bind and activate a specific receptor.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] These molecules, also referred to as ligands, are chemically diverse, including ions (such as Na+, K+, and Ca2+), lipids (e.g. steroid, prostaglandin), peptides (e.g. insulin, ACTH), carbohydrates, glycosylated proteins (proteoglycans), nucleic acids, etc.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Peptide and lipid ligands are particularly important, as most hormones belong to these classes of chemicals.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Peptides are usually polar, hydrophilic molecules.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] As such they are unable to diffuse freely across the bi-lipid layer of the plasma membrane, so their action is mediated by a cell membrane bound receptor.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] On the other hand, liposoluble chemicals such as steroid hormones, can diffuse passively across the plasma membrane and interact with intracellular receptors.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Cell signaling can be classified as autocrine, intracrine, juxtacrine, paracrine, or endocrine.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Autocrine signaling occurs when the chemical signal acts on the same cell that produced the signaling chemical.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Intracrine signaling occurs when the chemical signal produced by a cell acts on receptors located in the cytoplasm or nucleus of the same cell.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Juxtacrine signaling occurs between physically adjacent cells.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Paracrine signaling occurs between nearby cells.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Endocrine signaling occurs between distant cells, with the chemical signal (hormone) usually carried by the blood.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Receptors are complex proteins or tightly bound multimer of proteins, located in the plasma membrane or within the interior of the cell such as in the cytoplasm, organelles, and nucleus.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Receptors have the ability to detect a signal either by binding to a specific chemical or by undergoing a conformational change when interacting with physical agents.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] It is the specificity of the chemical interaction between a given ligand and its receptor that confers the ability to trigger a specific cellular response.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Receptors can be broadly classified into cell membrane receptors and intracellular receptors.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Cell membrane receptors can be further classified into ion channel linked receptors, G-Protein coupled receptors and enzyme linked receptors.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Intracellular receptors have a different mechanism of action.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] They usually bind to lipid soluble ligands that diffuse passively through the plasma membrane such as steroid hormones.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] These ligands bind to specific cytoplasmic transporters that shuttle the hormone-transporter complex inside the nucleus where specific genes are activated and the synthesis of specific proteins is promoted.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] The effector component of the signaling pathway begins with signal transduction.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] In this process, the signal, by interacting with the receptor, starts a series of molecular events within the cell leading to the final effect of the signaling process.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Typically the final effect consists in the activation of an ion channel (ligand-gated ion channel) or the initiation of a second messenger system cascade that propagates the signal through the cell.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Second messenger systems can amplify or modulate a signal, in which activation of a few receptors results in multiple secondary messengers being activated, thereby amplifying the initial signal (the first messenger).
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] The downstream effects of these signaling pathways may include additional enzymatic activities such as proteolytic cleavage, phosphorylation, methylation, and ubiquitinylation.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Signaling molecules can be synthesized from various biosynthetic pathways and released through passive or active transports, or even from cell damage.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Each cell is programmed to respond to specific extracellular signal molecules, and is the basis of development, tissue repair, immunity, and homeostasis.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Errors in signaling interactions may cause diseases such as cancer, autoimmunity, and diabetes.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] In many small organisms such as bacteria, quorum sensing enables individuals to begin an activity only when the population is sufficiently large.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] This signaling between cells was first observed in the marine bacterium *Aliivibrio fischeri*, which produces light when the population is dense enough.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] The mechanism involves the production and detection of a signaling molecule, and the regulation of gene transcription in response.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Quorum sensing operates in both gram-positive and gram-negative bacteria, and both within and between species.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] In slime molds, individual cells aggregate together to form fruiting bodies and eventually spores, under the influence of a chemical signal, known as an acrasin.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] The individuals move by chemotaxis, i.e. they are attracted by the chemical gradient.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Some species use cyclic AMP as the signal; others such as *Polysphondylium violaceum* use a dipeptide known as glorin.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] In plants and animals, signaling between cells occurs either through release into the extracellular space, divided in paracrine signaling (over short distances) and endocrine signaling (over long distances), or by direct contact, known as juxtacrine signaling such as notch signaling.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Autocrine signaling is a special case of paracrine signaling where the secreting cell has the ability to respond to the secreted signaling molecule.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Synaptic signaling is a special case of paracrine signaling (for chemical synapses) or juxtacrine signaling (for electrical synapses) between neurons and target cells.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Many cell signals are carried by molecules that are released by one cell and move to make contact with another cell.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Signaling molecules can belong to several chemical classes: lipids, phospholipids, amino acids, monoamines, proteins, glycoproteins, or gases.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Signaling molecules binding surface receptors are generally large and hydrophilic (e.g.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] In animal cells, specialized endocrine cells release these hormones and send them through the circulatory system to other parts of the body.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] They then reach target cells, which can recognize and respond to the hormones and produce a result.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] This is also known as endocrine signaling.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Plant growth regulators, or plant hormones, move through cells or by diffusing through the air as a gas to reach their targets.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Hydrogen sulfide is produced in small amounts by some cells of the human body and has a number of biological signaling functions.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Only two other such gases are currently known to act as signaling molecules in the human body: nitric oxide and carbon monoxide.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Exocytosis is the process by which a cell transports molecules such as neurotransmitters and proteins out of the cell.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] As an active transport mechanism, exocytosis requires the use of energy to transport material.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Exocytosis and its counterpart, endocytosis, the process that brings substances into the cell, are used by all cells because most chemical substances important to them are large polar molecules that cannot pass through the hydrophobic portion of the cell membrane by passive transport.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Exocytosis is the process by which a large amount of molecules are released; thus it is a form of bulk transport.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Exocytosis occurs via secretory portals at the cell plasma membrane called porosomes.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Porosomes are permanent cup-shaped lipoprotein structures at the cell plasma membrane, where secretory vesicles transiently dock and fuse to release intra-vesicular contents from the cell.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] In the context of neurotransmission, neurotransmitters are typically released from synaptic vesicles into the synaptic cleft via exocytosis; however, neurotransmitters can also be released via reverse transport through membrane transport proteins.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Autocrine signaling involves a cell secreting a hormone or chemical messenger (called the autocrine agent) that binds to autocrine receptors on that same cell, leading to changes in the cell itself.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] This can be contrasted with paracrine signaling, intracrine signaling, or classical endocrine signaling.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] In intracrine signaling, the signaling chemicals are produced inside the cell and bind to cytosolic or nuclear receptors within the cell.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] This type of signaling sets it apart from the other cell signaling mechanisms such as autocrine signaling.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] In both autocrine and intracrine signaling, the signal has an effect on the cell that produced it.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Juxtacrine signaling is a type of cell–cell or cell–extracellular matrix signaling in multicellular organisms that requires close contact.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] A communicating gap junction links the intracellular compartments of two adjacent cells, allowing transit of relatively small molecules.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] An extracellular matrix glycoprotein and a membrane protein interact.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Additionally, in unicellular organisms such as bacteria, juxtacrine signaling means interactions by membrane contact.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Juxtacrine signaling has been observed for some growth factors, cytokine and chemokine cellular signals, playing an important role in the immune response.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Juxtacrine signalling via direct membrane contacts is also present between neuronal cell bodies and motile processes of microglia both during development, and in the adult brain.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] In paracrine signaling, a cell produces a signal to induce changes in nearby cells, altering the behaviour of those cells.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Signaling molecules known as paracrine factors diffuse over a relatively short distance (local action), as opposed to cell signaling by endocrine factors, hormones which travel considerably longer distances via the circulatory system; juxtacrine interactions; and autocrine signaling.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Cells that produce paracrine factors secrete them into the immediate extracellular environment.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Factors then travel to nearby cells in which the gradient of factor received determines the outcome.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] However, the exact distance that paracrine factors can travel is not certain.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Paracrine signals such as retinoic acid target only cells in the vicinity of the emitting cell.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Neurotransmitters represent another example of a paracrine signal.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Some signaling molecules can function as both a hormone and a neurotransmitter.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] For example, epinephrine and norepinephrine can function as hormones when released from the adrenal gland and are transported to the heart by way of the blood stream.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Norepinephrine can also be produced by neurons to function as a neurotransmitter within the brain.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Estrogen can be released by the ovary and function as a hormone or act locally via paracrine or autocrine signaling.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Although paracrine signaling elicits a diverse array of responses in the induced cells, most paracrine factors utilize a relatively streamlined set of receptors and pathways.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] In fact, different organs in the body - even between different species - are known to utilize a similar sets of paracrine factors in differential development.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] The highly conserved receptors and pathways can be organized into four major families based on similar structures: fibroblast growth factor (FGF) family, Hedgehog family, Wnt family, and TGF-β superfamily.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Binding of a paracrine factor to its respective receptor initiates signal transduction cascades, eliciting different responses.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Cells receive information from their neighbors through a class of proteins known as receptors.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Receptors may bind with some molecules (ligands) or may interact with physical agents like light, mechanical temperature, pressure, etc.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Signaling molecules interact with a target cell as a ligand to cell surface receptors, and/or by entering into the cell through its membrane or endocytosis for intracrine signaling.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] This generally results in the activation of second messengers, leading to various physiological effects.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] In many mammals, early embryo cells exchange signals with cells of the uterus.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] In the human gastrointestinal tract, bacteria exchange signals with each other and with human epithelial and immune system cells.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] For the yeast *Saccharomyces cerevisiae* during mating, some cells send a peptide signal (mating factor pheromones) into their environment.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] The mating factor peptide may bind to a cell surface receptor on other yeast cells and induce them to prepare for mating.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Cell surface receptors play an essential role in the biological systems of single- and multi-cellular organisms and malfunction or damage to these proteins is associated with cancer, heart disease, and asthma.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] These trans-membrane receptors are able to transmit information from outside the cell to the inside because they change conformation when a specific ligand binds to it.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] There are three major types: Ion channel linked receptors, G protein–coupled receptors, and enzyme-linked receptors.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Ion channel linked receptors are a group of transmembrane ion-channel proteins which open to allow ions such as Na+, K+, Ca2+, and/or Cl− to pass through the membrane in response to the binding of a chemical messenger (i.e. a ligand), such as a neurotransmitter.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] When a presynaptic neuron is excited, it releases a neurotransmitter from vesicles into the synaptic cleft.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] The neurotransmitter then binds to receptors located on the postsynaptic neuron.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] If these receptors are ligand-gated ion channels (LICs), a resulting conformational change opens the ion channels, which leads to a flow of ions across the cell membrane.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] This, in turn, results in either a depolarization, for an excitatory receptor response, or a hyperpolarization, for an inhibitory response.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] These receptor proteins are typically composed of at least two different domains: a transmembrane domain which includes the ion pore, and an extracellular domain which includes the ligand binding location (an allosteric binding site).
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] This modularity has enabled a 'divide and conquer' approach to finding the structure of the proteins (crystallising each domain separately).
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] The function of such receptors located at synapses is to convert the chemical signal of presynaptically released neurotransmitter directly and very quickly into a postsynaptic electrical signal.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Many LICs are additionally modulated by allosteric ligands, by channel blockers, ions, or the membrane potential.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] LICs are classified into three superfamilies which lack evolutionary relationship: cys-loop receptors, ionotropic glutamate receptors and ATP-gated channels.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] G protein-coupled receptors are a large group of evolutionarily-related proteins that are cell surface receptors that detect molecules outside the cell and activate cellular responses.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Coupling with G proteins, they are also called seven-transmembrane receptors because they pass through the cell membrane seven times.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] The G-protein acts as a "middle man" transferring the signal from its activated receptor to its target and therefore indirectly regulates that target protein.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Ligands can bind either to extracellular N-terminus and loops (e.g. glutamate receptors) or to the binding site within transmembrane helices (Rhodopsin-like family).
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] They are all activated by agonists although a spontaneous auto-activation of an empty receptor can also be observed.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] G protein-coupled receptors are found only in eukaryotes, including yeast, choanoflagellates, and animals.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] The ligands that bind and activate these receptors include light-sensitive compounds, odors, pheromones, hormones, and neurotransmitters, and vary in size from small molecules to peptides to large proteins.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] G protein-coupled receptors are involved in many diseases.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] There are two principal signal transduction pathways involving the G-protein coupled receptors: cAMP signal pathway and phosphatidylinositol signal pathway.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] When a ligand binds to the GPCR it causes a conformational change in the GPCR, which allows it to act as a guanine nucleotide exchange factor (GEF).
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] The GPCR can then activate an associated G protein by exchanging the GDP bound to the G protein for a GTP.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] The G protein's α subunit, together with the bound GTP, can then dissociate from the β and γ subunits to further affect intracellular signaling proteins or target functional proteins directly depending on the α subunit type (Gαs, Gαi/o, Gαq/11, Gα12/13).
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] G protein-coupled receptors are an important drug target and approximately 34% of all Food and Drug Administration (FDA) approved drugs target 108 members of this family.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] The global sales volume for these drugs is estimated to be 180 billion US dollars as of 2018.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] The long ago discovered association between GPCRs and many endogenous and exogenous substances, resulting in e.g. analgesia, is another dynamically developing field of pharmaceutical research.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Enzyme-linked receptors (or catalytic receptors) are transmembrane receptors that, upon activation by an extracellular ligand, causes enzymatic activity on the intracellular side.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Hence a catalytic receptor is an integral membrane protein possessing both enzymatic, catalytic, and receptor functions.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] They have two important domains, an extra-cellular ligand binding domain and an intracellular domain, which has a catalytic function; and a single transmembrane helix.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] The signaling molecule binds to the receptor on the outside of the cell and causes a conformational change on the catalytic function located on the receptor inside the cell.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Intracellular receptors exist freely in the cytoplasm, nucleus, or can be bound to organelles or membranes.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] For example, the presence of nuclear and mitochondrial receptors is well documented.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] The binding of a ligand to the intracellular receptor typically induces a response in the cell.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Intracellular receptors often have a level of specificity, this allows the receptors to initiate certain responses when bound to a corresponding ligand.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Intracellular receptors typically act on lipid soluble molecules.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] The receptors bind to a group of DNA binding proteins.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Upon binding, the receptor-ligand complex translocates to the nucleus where they can alter patterns of gene expression.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Steroid hormone receptors are found in the nucleus, cytosol, and also on the plasma membrane of target cells.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] They are generally intracellular receptors (typically cytoplasmic or nuclear) and initiate signal transduction for steroid hormones which lead to changes in gene expression over a time period of hours to days.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] The best studied steroid hormone receptors are members of the nuclear receptor subfamily 3 (NR3) that include receptors for estrogen (group NR3A) and 3-ketosteroids (group NR3C).
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] In addition to nuclear receptors, several G protein-coupled receptors and ion channels act as cell surface receptors for certain steroid hormones.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Receptor mediated endocytosis is a common way of turning receptors "off".
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Endocytic down regulation is regarded as a means for reducing receptor signaling.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] The process involves the binding of a ligand to the receptor, which then triggers the formation of coated pits, the coated pits transform to coated vesicles and are transported to the endosome.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Receptor Phosphorylation is another type of receptor down-regulation.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Biochemical changes can reduce receptor affinity for a ligand.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Reducing the sensitivity of the receptor is a result of receptors being occupied for a long time.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] This results in a receptor adaptation in which the receptor no longer responds to the signaling molecule.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Many receptors have the ability to change in response to ligand concentration.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] When binding to the signaling molecule, the receptor protein changes in some way and starts the process of transduction, which can occur in a single step or as a series of changes in a sequence of different molecules (called a signal transduction pathway).
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] The molecules that compose these pathways are known as relay molecules.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] The multistep process of the transduction stage is often composed of the activation of proteins by addition or removal of phosphate groups or even the release of other small molecules or ions that can act as messengers.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] The amplification of a signal is one of the benefits to this multiple step sequence.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Other benefits include more opportunities for regulation than simpler systems do and the fine-tuning of the response, in both unicellular and multicellular organisms.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] In some cases, receptor activation caused by ligand binding to a receptor is directly coupled to the cell's response to the ligand.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] For example, the neurotransmitter GABA can activate a cell surface receptor that is part of an ion channel.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] GABA binding to a GABAA receptor on a neuron opens a chloride-selective ion channel that is part of the receptor.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] GABAA receptor activation allows negatively charged chloride ions to move into the neuron, which inhibits the ability of the neuron to produce action potentials.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] However, for many cell surface receptors, ligand-receptor interactions are not directly linked to the cell's response.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] The activated receptor must first interact with other proteins inside the cell before the ultimate physiological effect of the ligand on the cell's behavior is produced.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Often, the behavior of a chain of several interacting cell proteins is altered following receptor activation.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] The entire set of cell changes induced by receptor activation is called a signal transduction mechanism or pathway.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] A more complex signal transduction pathway is the MAPK/ERK pathway, which involves changes of protein–protein interactions inside the cell, induced by an external signal.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Many growth factors bind to receptors at the cell surface and stimulate cells to progress through the cell cycle and divide.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Several of these receptors are kinases that start to phosphorylate themselves and other proteins when binding to a ligand.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] This phosphorylation can generate a binding site for a different protein and thus induce protein–protein interaction.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] In this case, the ligand (called epidermal growth factor, or EGF) binds to the receptor (called EGFR).
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] This activates the receptor to phosphorylate itself.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] The phosphorylated receptor binds to an adaptor protein (GRB2), which couples the signal to further downstream signaling processes.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] For example, one of the signal transduction pathways that are activated is called the mitogen-activated protein kinase (MAPK) pathway.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] The signal transduction component labeled as "MAPK" in the pathway was originally called "ERK," so the pathway is called the MAPK/ERK pathway.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] The MAPK protein is an enzyme, a protein kinase that can attach phosphate to target proteins such as the transcription factor MYC and, thus, alter gene transcription and, ultimately, cell cycle progression.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Many cellular proteins are activated downstream of the growth factor receptors (such as EGFR) that initiate this signal transduction pathway.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Some signaling transduction pathways respond differently, depending on the amount of signaling received by the cell.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] For instance, the hedgehog protein activates different genes, depending on the amount of hedgehog protein present.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Complex multi-component signal transduction pathways provide opportunities for feedback, signal amplification, and interactions inside one cell between multiple signals and signaling pathways.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] A specific cellular response is the result of the transduced signal in the final stage of cell signaling.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] This response can essentially be any cellular activity that is present in a body.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] It can spur the rearrangement of the cytoskeleton, or even as catalysis by an enzyme.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] These three steps of cell signaling all ensure that the right cells are behaving as told, at the right time, and in synchronization with other cells and their own functions within the organism.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] At the end, the end of a signal pathway leads to the regulation of cellular activity.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] This response can take place in the nucleus or in the cytoplasm of the cell.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] A majority of signaling pathways control protein synthesis by turning certain genes on and off in the nucleus.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] In unicellular organisms such as bacteria, signaling can be used to 'activate' peers from a dormant state, enhance virulence, defend against bacteriophages, etc.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] In quorum sensing, which is also found in social insects, the multiplicity of individual signals has the potentiality to create a positive feedback loop, generating coordinated response.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] In this context, the signaling molecules are called autoinducers.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] This signaling mechanism may have been involved in evolution from unicellular to multicellular organisms.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Bacteria also use contact-dependent signaling, notably to limit their growth.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Signaling molecules used by multicellular organisms are often called pheromones.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] They can have such purposes as alerting against danger, indicating food supply, or assisting in reproduction.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Notch is a cell surface protein that functions as a receptor.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Animals have a small set of genes that code for signaling proteins that interact specifically with Notch receptors and stimulate a response in cells that express Notch on their surface.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Molecules that activate (or, in some cases, inhibit) receptors can be classified as hormones, neurotransmitters, cytokines, and growth factors, in general called receptor ligands.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Ligand receptor interactions such as that of the Notch receptor interaction, are known to be the main interactions responsible for cell signaling mechanisms and communication.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Notch acts as a receptor for ligands that are expressed on adjacent cells.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] While some receptors are cell-surface proteins, others are found inside cells.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] For example, estrogen is a hydrophobic molecule that can pass through the lipid bilayer of the membranes.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] As part of the endocrine system, intracellular estrogen receptors from a variety of cell types (such as ovary, prostate, lung, cardiovascular and central nervous systems) can be activated by estrogen produced in the ovaries.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] In the case of Notch-mediated signaling, the signal transduction mechanism can be relatively simple.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] As shown in Figure 2, the activation of Notch can cause the Notch protein to be altered by a protease.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Part of the Notch protein is released from the cell surface membrane and takes part in gene regulation.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Cell signaling research involves studying the spatial and temporal dynamics of both receptors and the components of signaling pathways that are activated by receptors in various cell types.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] Emerging methods for single-cell mass-spectrometry analysis promise to enable studying signal transduction with single-cell resolution.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] In notch signaling, direct contact between cells allows for precise control of cell differentiation during embryonic development.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] In the worm *Caenorhabditis elegans*, two cells of the developing gonad each have an equal chance of terminally differentiating or becoming a uterine precursor cell that continues to divide.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] The choice of which cell continues to divide is controlled by competition of cell surface signals.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] One cell will happen to produce more of a cell surface protein that activates the Notch receptor on the adjacent cell.
[src:signal-transduction/cell-signaling] This activates a feedback loop or system that reduces Notch expression in the cell that will differentiate and that increases Notch on the surface of the cell that continues as a stem cell.
[src:signal-transduction/cyclic-adenosine-monophosphate] Earl Sutherland of Vanderbilt University won a Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1971 "for his discoveries concerning the mechanisms of the action of hormones", especially epinephrine, via second messengers (such as cyclic adenosine monophosphate, cyclic AMP).
[src:signal-transduction/cyclic-adenosine-monophosphate] The synthesis of cAMP is stimulated by trophic hormones that bind to receptors on the cell surface. cAMP levels reach maximal levels within minutes and decrease gradually over an hour in cultured cells.
[src:signal-transduction/cyclic-adenosine-monophosphate] Cyclic AMP is synthesized from ATP by adenylyl cyclase located on the inner side of the plasma membrane and anchored at various locations in the interior of the cell.
[src:signal-transduction/cyclic-adenosine-monophosphate] Adenylyl cyclase is *activated* by a range of signaling molecules through the activation of adenylyl cyclase stimulatory G (Gs)-protein-coupled receptors.
[src:signal-transduction/cyclic-adenosine-monophosphate] Adenylyl cyclase is *inhibited* by agonists of adenylyl cyclase inhibitory G (Gi)-protein-coupled receptors.
[src:signal-transduction/cyclic-adenosine-monophosphate] Liver adenylyl cyclase responds more strongly to glucagon, and muscle adenylyl cyclase responds more strongly to adrenaline.
[src:signal-transduction/cyclic-adenosine-monophosphate] cAMP decomposition into AMP is catalyzed by the enzyme phosphodiesterase.
[src:signal-transduction/cyclic-adenosine-monophosphate] cAMP is a second messenger, used for intracellular signal transduction, such as transferring into cells the effects of hormones like glucagon and adrenaline, which cannot pass through the plasma membrane.
[src:signal-transduction/cyclic-adenosine-monophosphate] It is also involved in the activation of protein kinases.
[src:signal-transduction/cyclic-adenosine-monophosphate] In addition, cAMP binds to and regulates the function of ion channels such as the HCN channels and a few other cyclic nucleotide-binding proteins such as Epac1 and RAPGEF2.
[src:signal-transduction/cyclic-adenosine-monophosphate] cAMP is associated with kinases function in several biochemical processes, including the regulation of glycogen, sugar, and lipid metabolism.
[src:signal-transduction/cyclic-adenosine-monophosphate] In eukaryotes, cyclic AMP works by activating protein kinase A (PKA, or cAMP-dependent protein kinase).
[src:signal-transduction/cyclic-adenosine-monophosphate] PKA is normally inactive as a tetrameric holoenzyme, consisting of two catalytic and two regulatory units (C2R2), with the regulatory units blocking the catalytic centers of the catalytic units.
[src:signal-transduction/cyclic-adenosine-monophosphate] Cyclic AMP binds to specific locations on the regulatory units of the protein kinase, and causes dissociation between the regulatory and catalytic subunits, thus enabling those catalytic units to phosphorylate substrate proteins.
[src:signal-transduction/cyclic-adenosine-monophosphate] The active subunits catalyze the transfer of phosphate from ATP to specific serine or threonine residues of protein substrates.
[src:signal-transduction/cyclic-adenosine-monophosphate] The phosphorylated proteins may act directly on the cell's ion channels, or may become activated or inhibited enzymes.
[src:signal-transduction/cyclic-adenosine-monophosphate] Protein kinase A can also phosphorylate specific proteins that bind to promoter regions of DNA, causing increases in transcription.
[src:signal-transduction/cyclic-adenosine-monophosphate] Not all protein kinases respond to cAMP.
[src:signal-transduction/cyclic-adenosine-monophosphate] Several classes of protein kinases, including protein kinase C, are not cAMP-dependent.
[src:signal-transduction/cyclic-adenosine-monophosphate] Further effects mainly depend on cAMP-dependent protein kinase, which vary based on the type of cell.
[src:signal-transduction/cyclic-adenosine-monophosphate] Still, there are some minor PKA-independent functions of cAMP, e.g., activation of calcium channels, providing a minor pathway by which growth hormone-releasing hormone causes a release of growth hormone.
[src:signal-transduction/cyclic-adenosine-monophosphate] However, the view that the majority of the effects of cAMP are controlled by PKA is an outdated one.
[src:signal-transduction/cyclic-adenosine-monophosphate] In 1998 a family of cAMP-sensitive proteins with guanine nucleotide exchange factor (GEF) activity was discovered.
[src:signal-transduction/cyclic-adenosine-monophosphate] These are termed Exchange proteins activated by cAMP (Epac) and the family comprises Epac1 and Epac2.
[src:signal-transduction/cyclic-adenosine-monophosphate] The mechanism of activation is similar to that of PKA: the GEF domain is usually masked by the N-terminal region containing the cAMP binding domain.
[src:signal-transduction/cyclic-adenosine-monophosphate] When cAMP binds, the domain dissociates and exposes the now-active GEF domain, allowing Epac to activate small Ras-like GTPase proteins, such as Rap1.
[src:signal-transduction/cyclic-adenosine-monophosphate] In the species *Dictyostelium discoideum*, cAMP acts outside the cell as a secreted signal.
[src:signal-transduction/cyclic-adenosine-monophosphate] The chemotactic aggregation of cells is organized by periodic waves of cAMP that propagate between cells over distances as large as several centimetres.
[src:signal-transduction/cyclic-adenosine-monophosphate] The waves are the result of a regulated production and secretion of extracellular cAMP and a spontaneous biological oscillator that initiates the waves at centers of territories.
[src:signal-transduction/cyclic-adenosine-monophosphate] In bacteria, the level of cAMP varies depending on the medium used for growth.
[src:signal-transduction/cyclic-adenosine-monophosphate] In particular, cAMP is low when glucose is the carbon source.
[src:signal-transduction/cyclic-adenosine-monophosphate] This occurs through inhibition of the cAMP-producing enzyme, adenylyl cyclase, as a side-effect of glucose transport into the cell.
[src:signal-transduction/cyclic-adenosine-monophosphate] The transcription factor cAMP receptor protein (CRP) also called CAP (catabolite gene activator protein) forms a complex with cAMP and thereby is activated to bind to DNA.
[src:signal-transduction/cyclic-adenosine-monophosphate] CRP-cAMP increases expression of a large number of genes, including some encoding enzymes that can supply energy independent of glucose.
[src:signal-transduction/cyclic-adenosine-monophosphate] cAMP, for example, is involved in the positive regulation of the lac operon.
[src:signal-transduction/cyclic-adenosine-monophosphate] In an environment with a low glucose concentration, cAMP accumulates and binds to the allosteric site on CRP (cAMP receptor protein), a transcription activator protein.
[src:signal-transduction/cyclic-adenosine-monophosphate] The protein assumes its active shape and binds to a specific site upstream of the lac promoter, making it easier for RNA polymerase to bind to the adjacent promoter to start transcription of the lac operon, increasing the rate of lac operon transcription.
[src:signal-transduction/cyclic-adenosine-monophosphate] With a high glucose concentration, the cAMP concentration decreases, and the CRP disengages from the lac operon.
[src:signal-transduction/cyclic-adenosine-monophosphate] Some research has suggested that a deregulation of cAMP pathways and an aberrant activation of cAMP-controlled genes is linked to the growth of some cancers.
[src:signal-transduction/cyclic-adenosine-monophosphate] Research suggests that cAMP affects the function of higher-order thinking in the prefrontal cortex through its regulation of ion channels called hyperpolarization-activated cyclic nucleotide-gated channels (HCN).
[src:signal-transduction/cyclic-adenosine-monophosphate] HCN channels will open when exposed to cAMP.
[src:signal-transduction/cyclic-adenosine-monophosphate] Once the HCN channel is open, the electrical activity within the neuron is disrupted and the cell becomes less responsive.
[src:signal-transduction/cyclic-adenosine-monophosphate] This interferes with the function of the prefrontal cortex in working memory tasks.
[src:signal-transduction/cyclic-adenosine-monophosphate] Inhibition of cAMP has been observed to improve spatial working memory.
[src:signal-transduction/cyclic-adenosine-monophosphate] cAMP is involved in activation of trigeminocervical system leading to neurogenic inflammation and causing migraine.
[src:signal-transduction/cyclic-adenosine-monophosphate] Disrupted functioning of cAMP has been noted as one of the mechanisms of several bacterial exotoxins.
[src:signal-transduction/cyclic-adenosine-monophosphate] Forskolin is commonly used as a tool in biochemistry to raise levels of cAMP in the study and research of cell physiology.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] G protein-coupled receptors are found only in eukaryotes, including yeast, and choanoflagellates.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] The ligands that bind and activate these receptors include light-sensitive compounds, odors, pheromones, hormones, and neurotransmitters.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] They vary in size from small molecules to peptides, to large proteins.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] GPCRs are an important drug target, and approximately 34% of all Food and Drug Administration (FDA) approved drugs target 108 members of this family.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] The long ago discovered association between GPCRs and many endogenous and exogenous substances, resulting in e.g. analgesia, is another dynamically developing field of the pharmaceutical research.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] With the determination of the first structure of the complex between a G-protein coupled receptor (GPCR) and a G-protein trimer (Gαβγ) in 2011 a new chapter of GPCR research was opened for structural investigations of global switches with more than one protein being investigated.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] The previous breakthroughs involved determination of the crystal structure of the first GPCR, rhodopsin, in 2000 and the crystal structure of the first GPCR with a diffusible ligand (β2AR) in 2007.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] The way in which the seven transmembrane helices of a GPCR are arranged into a bundle was suspected based on the low-resolution model of frog rhodopsin from cryogenic electron microscopy studies of the two-dimensional crystals.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] The crystal structure of rhodopsin, that came up three years later, was not a surprise apart from the presence of an additional cytoplasmic helix H8 and a precise location of a loop covering retinal binding site.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] However, it provided a scaffold which was hoped to be a universal template for homology modeling and drug design for other GPCRs – a notion that proved to be too optimistic.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Results 7 years later were surprising because the crystallization of β2-adrenergic receptor (β2AR) with a diffusible ligand revealed quite a different shape of the receptor extracellular side than that of rhodopsin.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] This area is important because it is responsible for the ligand binding and is targeted by many drugs.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Moreover, the ligand binding site was much more spacious than in the rhodopsin structure and was open to the exterior.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] In the other receptors crystallized shortly afterwards the binding side was even more easily accessible to the ligand.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] New structures complemented with biochemical investigations uncovered mechanisms of action of molecular switches which modulate the structure of the receptor leading to activation states for agonists or to complete or partial inactivation states for inverse agonists.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] The 2012 Nobel Prize in Chemistry was awarded to Brian Kobilka and Robert Lefkowitz for their work that was "crucial for understanding how G protein-coupled receptors function".
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] There have been at least seven other Nobel Prizes awarded for some aspect of G protein–mediated signaling.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] As of 2012, two of the top ten global best-selling drugs (Advair Diskus and Abilify) act by targeting G protein-coupled receptors.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] The exact size of the GPCR superfamily is unknown, but at least 831 different human genes (or about 4% of the entire protein-coding genome) have been predicted to code for them from genome sequence analysis.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Although numerous classification schemes have been proposed, the superfamily was classically divided into three main classes (A, B, and C) with no detectable shared sequence homology between classes.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] The largest class by far is class A, which accounts for nearly 85% of the GPCR genes.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Of class A GPCRs, over half of these are predicted to encode olfactory receptors, while the remaining receptors are liganded by known endogenous compounds or are classified as orphan receptors.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Despite the lack of sequence homology between classes, all GPCRs have a common structure and mechanism of signal transduction.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] The very large rhodopsin A group has been further subdivided into 19 subgroups (A1-A19).
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] More recently, an alternative classification system called GRAFS (Glutamate, Rhodopsin, *Adhesion*, Frizzled/Taste2, Secretin) has been proposed for vertebrate GPCRs.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] They correspond to classical classes C, A, B2, F, and B.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] An early study based on available DNA sequence suggested that the human genome encodes roughly 750 G protein-coupled receptors, about 350 of which detect hormones, growth factors, and other endogenous ligands.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Approximately 150 of the GPCRs found in the human genome have unknown functions.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Some web-servers and bioinformatics prediction methods have been used for predicting the classification of GPCRs according to their amino acid sequence alone, by means of the pseudo amino acid composition approach.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] GPCRs are involved in a wide variety of physiological processes.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] The gustatory sense (taste): GPCRs in taste cells mediate release of gustducin in response to bitter-, umami- and sweet-tasting substances.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Behavioral and mood regulation: G protein-coupled receptors in the mammalian brain bind several different neurotransmitters, including serotonin, dopamine, histamine, noradrenaline, and GABA.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Notable exceptions include GABAA receptor, 5-HT3 serotonin receptor and glutamate receptors (NMDAR, AMPAR and kainate receptor), which are ion channels.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Regulation of immune system activity and inflammation: chemokine receptors bind ligands that mediate intercellular communication between cells of the immune system; receptors such as histamine receptors bind inflammatory mediators and engage target cell types in the inflammatory response.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] GPCRs are also involved in immune-modulation, e. g. regulating interleukin induction or suppressing TLR-induced immune responses from T cells.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Autonomic nervous system transmission: Both the sympathetic and parasympathetic nervous systems are regulated by GPCR pathways.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] The involved receptors include adrenergic receptors (α1, α2, β1, β2 and β3, of which β2 is notable for being the first GPCR to have the crystal structure determined) for the sympathetic nervous system and muscarinic acetylcholine receptors for the parasympathetic nervous system.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Adrenergic receptor ligands are known to modulate blood pressure and heart rate, while muscarinic antagonists produce a host of symptoms such as pupil dilation, urinary retention, constipation and dry mouth that are directly related to inhibition of the parasympathetic nervous system.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Cell density sensing: A novel GPCR role in regulating cell density sensing.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Homeostasis modulation (e.g., water balance).
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Involved in growth and metastasis of some types of tumors.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Used in the endocrine system for peptide and amino-acid derivative hormones that bind to GCPRs on the cell membrane of a target cell.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] This activates cAMP, which in turn activates several kinases, allowing for a cellular response, such as transcription.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] GPCRs are integral membrane proteins that possess seven membrane-spanning domains or transmembrane helices.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] The extracellular parts of the receptor can be glycosylated.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] These extracellular loops also contain two highly conserved cysteine residues that form disulfide bonds to stabilize the receptor structure.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Some seven-transmembrane helix proteins (channelrhodopsin) that resemble GPCRs may contain ion channels, within their protein.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] In 2000, the first crystal structure of a mammalian GPCR, that of bovine rhodopsin (1F88), was solved.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] In 2007, the first structure of a human GPCR was solved This human β2-adrenergic receptor GPCR structure proved highly similar to the bovine rhodopsin.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] The structures of activated or agonist-bound GPCRs have also been determined.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] These structures indicate how ligand binding at the extracellular side of a receptor leads to conformational changes in the cytoplasmic side of the receptor.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] The biggest change is an outward movement of the cytoplasmic part of the 5th and 6th transmembrane helix (TM5 and TM6).
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] The structure of activated beta-2 adrenergic receptor in complex with Gs confirmed that the Gα binds to a cavity created by this movement.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] GPCRs exhibit a similar structure to some other proteins with seven transmembrane domains, such as microbial rhodopsins and adiponectin receptors 1 and 2 (ADIPOR1 and ADIPOR2).
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] However, these 7TMH (7-transmembrane helices) receptors and channels do not associate with G proteins.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] In addition, ADIPOR1 and ADIPOR2 are oriented oppositely to GPCRs in the membrane (i.e.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] GPCRs usually have an extracellular N-terminus, cytoplasmic C-terminus, whereas ADIPORs are inverted).
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] In terms of structure, GPCRs are characterized by an extracellular N-terminus, followed by seven transmembrane (7-TM) α-helices (TM-1 to TM-7) connected by three intracellular (IL-1 to IL-3) and three extracellular loops (EL-1 to EL-3), and finally an intracellular C-terminus.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] The GPCR arranges itself into a tertiary structure resembling a barrel, with the seven transmembrane helices forming a cavity within the plasma membrane that serves a ligand-binding domain that is often covered by EL-2.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Ligands may also bind elsewhere, however, as is the case for bulkier ligands (e.g., proteins or large peptides), which instead interact with the extracellular loops, or, as illustrated by the class C metabotropic glutamate receptors (mGluRs), the N-terminal tail.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] The class C GPCRs are distinguished by their large N-terminal tail, which also contains a ligand-binding domain.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Upon glutamate-binding to an mGluR, the N-terminal tail undergoes a conformational change that leads to its interaction with the residues of the extracellular loops and TM domains.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Inverse agonists and antagonists may also bind to a number of different sites, but the eventual effect must be prevention of this TM helix reorientation.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] The structure of the N- and C-terminal tails of GPCRs may also serve important functions beyond ligand-binding.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] For example, The C-terminus of M3 muscarinic receptors is sufficient, and the six-amino-acid polybasic (KKKRRK) domain in the C-terminus is necessary for its preassembly with Gq proteins.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] In particular, the C-terminus often contains serine (Ser) or threonine (Thr) residues that, when phosphorylated, increase the affinity of the intracellular surface for the binding of scaffolding proteins called β-arrestins (β-arr).
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Once bound, β-arrestins both sterically prevent G-protein coupling and may recruit other proteins, leading to the creation of signaling complexes involved in extracellular-signal regulated kinase (ERK) pathway activation or receptor endocytosis (internalization).
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] As the phosphorylation of these Ser and Thr residues often occurs as a result of GPCR activation, the β-arr-mediated G-protein-decoupling and internalization of GPCRs are important mechanisms of desensitization.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] In addition, internalized "mega-complexes" consisting of a single GPCR, β-arr(in the tail conformation), and heterotrimeric G protein exist and may account for protein signaling from endosomes.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] A final common structural theme among GPCRs is palmitoylation of one or more sites of the C-terminal tail or the intracellular loops.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Palmitoylation is the covalent modification of cysteine (Cys) residues via addition of hydrophobic acyl groups, and has the effect of targeting the receptor to cholesterol- and sphingolipid-rich microdomains of the plasma membrane called lipid rafts.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] As many of the downstream transducer and effector molecules of GPCRs (including those involved in negative feedback pathways) are also targeted to lipid rafts, this has the effect of facilitating rapid receptor signaling.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] GPCRs respond to extracellular signals mediated by a huge diversity of agonists, ranging from proteins to biogenic amines to protons, but all transduce this signal via a mechanism of G-protein coupling.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] This is made possible by a guanine-nucleotide exchange factor (GEF) domain primarily formed by a combination of IL-2 and IL-3 along with adjacent residues of the associated TM helices.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] The G protein-coupled receptor is activated by an external signal in the form of a ligand or other signal mediator.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] This creates a conformational change in the receptor, causing activation of a G protein.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Further effect depends on the type of G protein.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] G proteins are subsequently inactivated by GTPase activating proteins, known as RGS proteins.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] GPCRs that act as receptors for stimuli that have not yet been identified are known as orphan receptors.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] However, in contrast to other types of receptors that have been studied, wherein ligands bind externally to the membrane, the ligands of GPCRs typically bind within the transmembrane domain.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] However, protease-activated receptors are activated by cleavage of part of their extracellular domain.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] The transduction of the signal through the membrane by the receptor is not completely understood.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] It is known that in the inactive state, the GPCR is bound to a heterotrimeric G protein complex.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Binding of an agonist to the GPCR results in a conformational change in the receptor that is transmitted to the bound Gα subunit of the heterotrimeric G protein via protein domain dynamics.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] The activated Gα subunit exchanges GTP in place of GDP which in turn triggers the dissociation of Gα subunit from the Gβγ dimer and from the receptor.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] The dissociated Gα and Gβγ subunits interact with other intracellular proteins to continue the signal transduction cascade while the freed GPCR is able to rebind to another heterotrimeric G protein to form a new complex that is ready to initiate another round of signal transduction.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] It is believed that a receptor molecule exists in a conformational equilibrium between active and inactive biophysical states.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] The binding of ligands to the receptor may shift the equilibrium toward the active receptor states.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Three types of ligands exist: Agonists are ligands that shift the equilibrium in favour of active states; inverse agonists are ligands that shift the equilibrium in favour of inactive states; and neutral antagonists are ligands that do not affect the equilibrium.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] It is not yet known how exactly the active and inactive states differ from each other.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] When the receptor is inactive, the GEF domain may be bound to an also inactive α-subunit of a heterotrimeric G-protein.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] These "G-proteins" are a trimer of α, β, and γ subunits (known as Gα, Gβ, and Gγ, respectively) that is rendered inactive when reversibly bound to Guanosine diphosphate (GDP) (or, alternatively, no guanine nucleotide) but active when bound to guanosine triphosphate (GTP).
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Upon receptor activation, the GEF domain, in turn, allosterically activates the G-protein by facilitating the exchange of a molecule of GDP for GTP at the G-protein's α-subunit.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] The cell maintains a 10:1 ratio of cytosolic GTP:GDP so exchange for GTP is ensured.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] At this point, the subunits of the G-protein dissociate from the receptor, as well as each other, to yield a Gα-GTP monomer and a tightly interacting Gβγ dimer, which are now free to modulate the activity of other intracellular proteins.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] The extent to which they may diffuse, however, is limited due to the palmitoylation of Gα and the presence of an isoprenoid moiety that has been covalently added to the C-termini of Gγ.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Because Gα also has slow GTP→GDP hydrolysis capability, the inactive form of the α-subunit (Gα-GDP) is eventually regenerated, thus allowing reassociation with a Gβγ dimer to form the "resting" G-protein, which can again bind to a GPCR and await activation.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] The rate of GTP hydrolysis is often accelerated due to the actions of another family of allosteric modulating proteins called regulators of G-protein signaling, or RGS proteins, which are a type of GTPase-activating protein, or GAP.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] In fact, many of the primary effector proteins (e.g., adenylate cyclases) that become activated/inactivated upon interaction with Gα-GTP also have GAP activity.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Thus, even at this early stage in the process, GPCR-initiated signaling has the capacity for self-termination.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] GPCRs downstream signals have been shown to possibly interact with integrin signals, such as FAK.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Integrin signaling will phosphorylate FAK, which can then decrease GPCR Gαs activity.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] If a receptor in an active state encounters a G protein, it may activate it.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Some evidence suggests that receptors and G proteins are actually pre-coupled.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] For example, binding of G proteins to receptors affects the receptor's affinity for ligands.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Further signal transduction depends on the type of G protein.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] The enzyme adenylate cyclase is an example of a cellular protein that can be regulated by a G protein, in this case the G protein Gs.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Adenylate cyclase activity is activated when it binds to a subunit of the activated G protein.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Activation of adenylate cyclase ends when the G protein returns to the GDP-bound state.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Adenylate cyclases (of which 9 membrane-bound and one cytosolic forms are known in humans) may also be activated or inhibited in other ways (e.g., Ca2+/calmodulin binding), which can modify the activity of these enzymes in an additive or synergistic fashion along with the G proteins.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] The signaling pathways activated through a GPCR are limited by the primary sequence and tertiary structure of the GPCR itself but ultimately determined by the particular conformation stabilized by a particular ligand, as well as the availability of transducer molecules.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Currently, GPCRs are considered to utilize two primary types of transducers: G-proteins and β-arrestins.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Because β-arr's have high affinity only to the phosphorylated form of most GPCRs (see above or below), the majority of signaling is ultimately dependent upon G-protein activation.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] However, the possibility for interaction does allow for G-protein-independent signaling to occur.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] There are three main G-protein-mediated signaling pathways, mediated by four sub-classes of Gα-proteins distinguished from each other by sequence homology (Gαs, Gαi/o, Gαq/11, and Gα12/13).
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Each sub-class of G-protein consists of multiple proteins, each the product of multiple genes or splice variations that may imbue them with differences ranging from subtle to distinct with regard to signaling properties, but in general they appear reasonably grouped into four classes.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Because the signal transducing properties of the various possible βγ combinations do not appear to radically differ from one another, these classes are defined according to the isoform of their α-subunit.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] While most GPCRs are capable of activating more than one Gα-subtype, they also show a preference for one subtype over another.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] When the subtype activated depends on the ligand that is bound to the GPCR, this is called functional selectivity (also known as agonist-directed trafficking, or conformation-specific agonism).
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] However, the binding of any single particular agonist may also initiate activation of multiple different G-proteins, as it may be capable of stabilizing more than one conformation of the GPCR's GEF domain, even over the course of a single interaction.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] In addition, a conformation that preferably activates one isoform of Gα may activate another if the preferred is less available.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Furthermore, feedback pathways may result in receptor modifications (e.g., phosphorylation) that alter the G-protein preference.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Regardless of these various nuances, the GPCR's preferred coupling partner is usually defined according to the G-protein most obviously activated by the endogenous ligand under most physiological or experimental conditions.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] The effector of the Gαq/11 pathway is phospholipase C-β (PLCβ), which catalyzes the cleavage of membrane-bound phosphatidylinositol 4,5-bisphosphate (PIP2) into the second messengers inositol (1,4,5) trisphosphate (IP3) and diacylglycerol (DAG).
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] IP3 acts on IP3 receptors found in the membrane of the endoplasmic reticulum (ER) to elicit Ca2+ release from the ER, while DAG diffuses along the plasma membrane where it may activate any membrane localized forms of a second ser/thr kinase called protein kinase C (PKC).
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Since many isoforms of PKC are also activated by increases in intracellular Ca2+, both these pathways can also converge on each other to signal through the same secondary effector.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Elevated intracellular Ca2+ also binds and allosterically activates proteins called calmodulins, which in turn activate cytosolic small GTPase, Rho.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Once bound to GTP, Rho can then go on to activate various proteins responsible for cytoskeleton regulation such as Rho-kinase (ROCK).
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Most GPCRs that couple to Gα12/13 also couple to other sub-classes, often Gαq/11.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] The above descriptions ignore the effects of Gβγ–signalling, which can also be important, in particular in the case of activated Gαi/o-coupled GPCRs.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] The primary effectors of Gβγ are various ion channels, such as G-protein-regulated inwardly rectifying K+ channels (GIRKs), P/Q- and N-type voltage-gated Ca2+ channels, as well as some isoforms of AC and PLC, along with some phosphoinositide-3-kinase (PI3K) isoforms.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Although they are classically thought of working only together, GPCRs may signal through G-protein-independent mechanisms, and heterotrimeric G-proteins may play functional roles independent of GPCRs.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] GPCRs may signal independently through many proteins already mentioned for their roles in G-protein-dependent signaling such as β-arrs, GRKs, and Srcs.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Such signaling has been shown to be physiologically relevant, for example, β-arrestin signaling mediated by the chemokine receptor CXCR3 was necessary for full efficacy chemotaxis of activated T cells.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] In addition, further scaffolding proteins involved in subcellular localization of GPCRs (e.g., PDZ-domain-containing proteins) may also act as signal transducers.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Most often the effector is a member of the MAPK family.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] In the late 1990s, evidence began accumulating to suggest that some GPCRs are able to signal without G proteins.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] In mammalian cells, the much-studied β2-adrenoceptor has been demonstrated to activate the ERK2 pathway after arrestin-mediated uncoupling of G-protein-mediated signaling.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Therefore, it seems likely that some mechanisms previously believed related purely to receptor desensitisation are actually examples of receptors switching their signaling pathway, rather than simply being switched off.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] In kidney cells, the bradykinin receptor B2 has been shown to interact directly with a protein tyrosine phosphatase.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] The presence of a tyrosine-phosphorylated ITIM (immunoreceptor tyrosine-based inhibitory motif) sequence in the B2 receptor is necessary to mediate this interaction and subsequently the antiproliferative effect of bradykinin.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Although it is a relatively immature area of research, it appears that heterotrimeric G-proteins may also take part in non-GPCR signaling.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] There may even be specific proteins of these classes whose primary function is as part of GPCR-independent pathways, termed activators of G-protein signalling (AGS).
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Both the ubiquity of these interactions and the importance of Gα vs.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Gβγ subunits to these processes are still unclear.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] There are two principal signal transduction pathways involving the G protein-linked receptors: the cAMP signal pathway and the phosphatidylinositol signal pathway.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] The cAMP signal transduction contains five main characters: stimulative hormone receptor (Rs) or inhibitory hormone receptor (Ri); stimulative regulative G-protein (Gs) or inhibitory regulative G-protein (Gi); adenylyl cyclase; protein kinase A (PKA); and cAMP phosphodiesterase.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Stimulative hormone receptor (Rs) is a receptor that can bind with stimulative signal molecules, while inhibitory hormone receptor (Ri) is a receptor that can bind with inhibitory signal molecules.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Stimulative regulative G-protein is a G-protein linked to stimulative hormone receptor (Rs), and its α subunit upon activation could stimulate the activity of an enzyme or other intracellular metabolism.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] On the contrary, inhibitory regulative G-protein is linked to an inhibitory hormone receptor, and its α subunit upon activation could inhibit the activity of an enzyme or other intracellular metabolism.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Adenylyl cyclase is a 12-transmembrane glycoprotein that catalyzes the conversion of ATP to cAMP with the help of cofactor Mg2+ or Mn2+.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] The cAMP produced is a second messenger in cellular metabolism and is an allosteric activator of protein kinase A.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Protein kinase A is an important enzyme in cell metabolism due to its ability to regulate cell metabolism by phosphorylating specific committed enzymes in the metabolic pathway.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] It can also regulate specific gene expression, cellular secretion, and membrane permeability.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] The protein enzyme contains two catalytic subunits and two regulatory subunits.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] When there is no cAMP, the complex is inactive.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] When cAMP binds to the regulatory subunits, their conformation is altered, causing the dissociation of the regulatory subunits, which activates protein kinase A and allows further biological effects.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] These signals then can be terminated by cAMP phosphodiesterase, which is an enzyme that degrades cAMP to 5'-AMP and inactivates protein kinase A.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] In the phosphatidylinositol signal pathway, the extracellular signal molecule binds with the G-protein receptor (Gq) on the cell surface and activates phospholipase C, which is located on the plasma membrane.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] The lipase hydrolyzes phosphatidylinositol 4,5-bisphosphate (PIP2) into two second messengers: inositol 1,4,5-trisphosphate (IP3) and diacylglycerol (DAG).
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] IP3 binds with the IP3 receptor in the membrane of the smooth endoplasmic reticulum and mitochondria to open Ca2+ channels.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] DAG helps activate protein kinase C (PKC), which phosphorylates many other proteins, changing their catalytic activities, leading to cellular responses.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] The kinase then phosphorylates target enzymes, regulating their activities.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] The two signal pathways are connected together by Ca2+-CaM, which is also a regulatory subunit of adenylyl cyclase and phosphodiesterase in the cAMP signal pathway.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] GPCRs become desensitized when exposed to their ligand for a long period of time.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] There are two recognized forms of desensitization: 1) homologous desensitization, in which the activated GPCR is downregulated; and 2) heterologous desensitization, wherein the activated GPCR causes downregulation of a different GPCR.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] The key reaction of this downregulation is the phosphorylation of the intracellular (or cytoplasmic) receptor domain by protein kinases.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Cyclic AMP-dependent protein kinases (protein kinase A) are activated by the signal chain coming from the G protein (that was activated by the receptor) via adenylate cyclase and cyclic AMP (cAMP).
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] In a *feedback mechanism*, these activated kinases phosphorylate the receptor.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] The longer the receptor remains active the more kinases are activated and the more receptors are phosphorylated.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] In β2-adrenoceptors, this phosphorylation results in the switching of the coupling from the Gs class of G-protein to the Gi class. cAMP-dependent PKA mediated phosphorylation can cause heterologous desensitisation in receptors other than those activated.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] The G protein-coupled receptor kinases (GRKs) are protein kinases that phosphorylate only active GPCRs.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] G-protein-coupled receptor kinases (GRKs) are key modulators of G-protein-coupled receptor (GPCR) signaling.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] They constitute a family of seven mammalian serine-threonine protein kinases that phosphorylate agonist-bound receptor.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] GRKs-mediated receptor phosphorylation rapidly initiates profound impairment of receptor signaling and desensitization.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Activity of GRKs and subcellular targeting is tightly regulated by interaction with receptor domains, G protein subunits, lipids, anchoring proteins and calcium-sensitive proteins.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] *Arrestin linking*: The phosphorylated receptor can be linked to *arrestin* molecules that prevent it from binding (and activating) G proteins, in effect switching it off for a short period of time.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] This mechanism is used, for example, with rhodopsin in retina cells to compensate for exposure to bright light.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] In many cases, arrestin's binding to the receptor is a prerequisite for translocation.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] For example, beta-arrestin bound to β2-adrenoreceptors acts as an adaptor for binding with clathrin, and with the beta-subunit of AP2 (clathrin adaptor molecules); thus, the arrestin here acts as a scaffold assembling the components needed for clathrin-mediated endocytosis of β2-adrenoreceptors.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] As mentioned above, G-proteins may terminate their own activation due to their intrinsic GTP→GDP hydrolysis capability.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] However, this reaction proceeds at a slow rate (≈0.02 times/sec) and, thus, it would take around 50 seconds for any single G-protein to deactivate if other factors did not come into play.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Indeed, there are around 30 isoforms of RGS proteins that, when bound to Gα through their GAP domain, accelerate the hydrolysis rate to ≈30 times/sec.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] This 1500-fold increase in rate allows for the cell to respond to external signals with high speed, as well as spatial resolution due to limited amount of second messenger that can be generated and limited distance a G-protein can diffuse in 0.03 seconds.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] For the most part, the RGS proteins are promiscuous in their ability to deactivate G-proteins, while which RGS is involved in a given signaling pathway seems more determined by the tissue and GPCR involved than anything else.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] In addition, RGS proteins have the additional function of increasing the rate of GTP-GDP exchange at GPCRs, (i.e., as a sort of co-GEF) further contributing to the time resolution of GPCR signaling.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] In addition, the GPCR may be desensitized itself.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] 2. the affinity for β-arrestin may be increased in a ligand occupation and GRK-independent manner through phosphorylation of different ser/thr sites (but also of IL-3 and the C-terminal tail) by PKC and PKA.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] These phosphorylations are often sufficient to impair G-protein coupling on their own as well.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] PKC/PKA may, instead, phosphorylate GRKs, which can also lead to GPCR phosphorylation and β-arrestin binding in an occupation-independent manner.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] These latter two mechanisms allow for desensitization of one GPCR due to the activities of others, or heterologous desensitization.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] GRKs may also have GAP domains and so may contribute to inactivation through non-kinase mechanisms as well.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] A combination of these mechanisms may also occur.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Once β-arrestin is bound to a GPCR, it undergoes a conformational change allowing it to serve as a scaffolding protein for an adaptor complex termed AP-2, which in turn recruits another protein called clathrin.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] If enough receptors in the local area recruit clathrin in this manner, they aggregate and the membrane buds inwardly as a result of interactions between the molecules of clathrin, in a process called opsonization.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Once the pit has been pinched off the plasma membrane due to the actions of two other proteins called amphiphysin and dynamin, it is now an endocytic vesicle.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] At this point, the adapter molecules and clathrin have dissociated, and the receptor is either trafficked back to the plasma membrane or targeted to lysosomes for degradation.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Another target of c-SRC are the dynamin molecules involved in endocytosis.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Dynamins polymerize around the neck of an incoming vesicle, and their phosphorylation by c-SRC provides the energy necessary for the conformational change allowing the final "pinching off" from the membrane.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Receptor desensitization is mediated through a combination phosphorylation, β-arr binding, and endocytosis as described above.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Downregulation occurs when endocytosed receptor is embedded in an endosome that is trafficked to merge with an organelle called a lysosome.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Because lysosomal membranes are rich in proton pumps, their interiors have low pH (≈4.8 vs. the pH≈7.2 cytosol), which acts to denature the GPCRs.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] In addition, lysosomes contain many degradative enzymes, including proteases, which can function only at such low pH, and so the peptide bonds joining the residues of the GPCR together may be cleaved.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Whether or not a given receptor is trafficked to a lysosome, detained in endosomes, or trafficked back to the plasma membrane depends on a variety of factors, including receptor type and magnitude of the signal.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] GPCR regulation is additionally mediated by gene transcription factors.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] These factors can increase or decrease gene transcription and thus increase or decrease the generation of new receptors (up- or down-regulation) that travel to the cell membrane.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] G-protein-coupled receptor oligomerisation is a widespread phenomenon.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] One of the best-studied examples is the metabotropic GABAB receptor.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] This so-called constitutive receptor is formed by heterodimerization of GABABR1 and GABABR2 subunits.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Expression of the GABABR1 without the GABABR2 in heterologous systems leads to retention of the subunit in the endoplasmic reticulum.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Expression of the GABABR2 subunit alone, meanwhile, leads to surface expression of the subunit, although with no functional activity (i.e., the receptor does not bind agonist and cannot initiate a response following exposure to agonist).
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Expression of the two subunits together leads to plasma membrane expression of functional receptor.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] It has been shown that GABABR2 binding to GABABR1 causes masking of a retention signal of functional receptors.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Signal transduction mediated by the superfamily of GPCRs dates back to the origin of multicellularity.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Mammalian-like GPCRs are found in fungi, and have been classified according to the GRAFS classification system based on GPCR fingerprints.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Identification of the superfamily members across the eukaryotic domain, and comparison of the family-specific motifs, have shown that the superfamily of GPCRs have a common origin.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Characteristic motifs indicate that three of the five GRAFS families, *Rhodopsin*, *Adhesion*, and *Frizzled*, evolved from the *Dictyostelium discoideum* cAMP receptors before the split of opisthokonts.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Later, the *Secretin* family evolved from the *Adhesion* GPCR receptor family before the split of nematodes.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Insect GPCRs appear to be in their own group and Taste2 is identified as descending from *Rhodopsin*.
[src:signal-transduction/g-protein-coupled-receptor] Note that the *Secretin*/*Adhesion* split is based on presumed function rather than signature, as the classical Class B (7tm_2, Pfam PF00002) is used to identify both in the studies.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] The **MAPK/ERK pathway** (also known as the **Ras-Raf-MEK-ERK pathway**) is a chain of proteins in the cell that communicates a signal from a receptor on the surface of the cell to the DNA in the nucleus of the cell.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] The signal starts when a signaling molecule binds to the receptor on the cell surface and ends when the DNA in the nucleus expresses a protein and produces some change in the cell, such as cell division.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] The pathway includes many proteins, such as mitogen-activated protein kinases (MAPKs), originally called extracellular signal-regulated kinases (ERKs), which communicate by adding phosphate groups to a neighboring protein (phosphorylating it), thereby acting as an "on" or "off" switch.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] When one of the proteins in the pathway is mutated, it can become stuck in the "on" or "off" position, a necessary step in the development of many cancers.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] In fact, components of the MAPK/ERK pathway were first discovered in cancer cells, and drugs that reverse the "on" or "off" switch are being investigated as cancer treatments.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] The signal that starts the MAPK/ERK pathway is the binding of extracellular mitogen to a cell surface receptor.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] This allows a Ras protein (a Small GTPase) to swap a GDP molecule for a GTP molecule, flipping the "on/off switch" of the pathway.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] The Ras protein can then activate MAP3K (e.g., Raf), which activates MAP2K, which activates MAPK.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] Finally, MAPK can activate a transcription factor, such as Myc.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] This process is described in more detail below.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] Receptor-linked tyrosine kinases, such as the epidermal growth factor receptor (EGFR), are activated by extracellular ligands, such as the epidermal growth factor (EGF).
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] Binding of EGF to the EGFR activates the tyrosine kinase activity of the cytoplasmic domain of the receptor.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] The EGFR becomes phosphorylated on tyrosine residues.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] Docking proteins such as GRB2 contain an SH2 domain that binds to the phosphotyrosine residues of the activated receptor.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] GRB2 binds to the guanine nucleotide exchange factor SOS by way of the two SH3 domains of GRB2.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] When the GRB2-SOS complex docks to phosphorylated EGFR, SOS becomes activated.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] Activated SOS then promotes the removal of GDP from a member of the Ras subfamily (most notably H-Ras or K-Ras).
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] The Ras protein can then bind GTP and become active.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] Apart from EGFR, other cell surface receptors that can activate this pathway via GRB2 include Trk A/B, Fibroblast growth factor receptor (FGFR) and PDGFR.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] Activated Ras then activates the protein kinase activity of a RAF kinase.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] The RAF kinase phosphorylates and activates a MAPK/ERK Kinase (MEK1 or MEK2).
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] The MEK phosphorylates and activates a mitogen-activated protein kinase (MAPK).
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] RAF and MAPK/ERK are both serine/threonine-specific protein kinases.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] MEK is a serine/tyrosine/threonine kinase.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] In a technical sense, RAF, MEK, and MAPK are all mitogen-activated kinases, as is MNK (see below).
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] MAPKs were originally called "extracellular signal-regulated kinases" (ERKs) and "microtubule associated protein kinases" (MAPKs).
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] One of the first proteins known to be phosphorylated by ERK was a microtubule-associated protein (MAP).
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] As discussed below, many additional targets for phosphorylation by MAPK were later found, and the protein was renamed "mitogen-activated protein kinase" (MAPK).
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] The series of kinases from RAF to MEK to MAPK is an example of a protein kinase cascade.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] Such series of kinases provide opportunities for feedback regulation and signal amplification.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] Three of the many proteins that are phosphorylated by MAPK are shown in the figure to the right.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] One effect of MAPK activation is to alter the translation of mRNA to proteins.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] MAPK phosphorylates the 40S ribosomal protein S6 kinase (RSK).
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] This activates RSK, which, in turn, phosphorylates ribosomal protein S6.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] Mitogen-activated protein kinases that phosphorylate ribosomal protein S6 were the first to be isolated.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] MAPK regulates the activities of several transcription factors.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] MAPK phosphorylates and activates MNK, which, in turn, phosphorylates CREB.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] MAPK also regulates the transcription of the C-Fos gene.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] By altering the levels and activities of transcription factors, MAPK leads to altered transcription of genes that are important for the cell cycle.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] The 22q11, 1q42, and 19p13 genes, by affecting the ERK pathway, are associated with schizophrenia, schizoaffective disorder, bipolar disorder, and migraines.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] The ERK pathway plays an important role of integrating external signals from the presence of mitogens such as epidermal growth factor (EGF) into signaling events promoting cell growth and proliferation in many mammalian cell types.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] In a simplified model, the presence of mitogens and growth factors trigger the activation of canonical receptor tyrosine kinases such as EGFR leading to their dimerization and subsequent activation of the small GTPase Ras.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] This then leads to a series of phosphorylation events downstream in the MAPK cascade (Raf-MEK-ERK) ultimately resulting in the phosphorylation and activation of ERK.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] The phosphorylation of ERK results in an activation of its kinase activity and leads to phosphorylation of its many downstream targets involved in regulation of cell proliferation.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] In most cells, some form of sustained ERK activity is required for cells to activate genes that induce cell cycle entry and suppress negative regulators of the cell cycle.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] Two such important targets include Cyclin D complexes with Cdk4 and Cdk6 (Cdk4/6) which are both phosphorylated by ERK.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] The transition from G1 to S phase is coordinated by the activity of Cyclin D-Cdk4/6, which increases during late G1 phase as cells prepare to enter S-phase in response to mitogens.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] Cdk4/6 activation contributes to hyper-phosphorylation and the subsequent destabilization of retinoblastoma protein (Rb).
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] Hypo-phosphorylated Rb, is normally bound to transcription factor E2F in early G1 and inhibits its transcriptional activity, preventing expression of S-phase entry genes including Cyclin E, Cyclin A2 and Emi1.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] ERK1/2 activation downstream of mitogen induced Ras signaling is necessary and sufficient to remove this cell cycle block and allow cells to progress to S-phase in most mammalian cells.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] The restriction point (R-point) marks the critical event when a mammalian cell commits to proliferation and becomes independent of growth stimulation.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] It is fundamental for normal differentiation and tissue homeostasis, and seems to be dysregulated in virtually all cancers.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] Although the R-point has been linked to various activities involved in the regulation of G1–S transition of the mammalian cell cycle, the underlying mechanism remains unclear.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] Using single-cell measurements, Yao et al., shows that the Rb–E2F pathway functions as a bistable switch to convert graded serum inputs into all-or-none E2F responses.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] Growth and mitogen signals transmitted downstream of the ERK pathway are incorporated into multiple positive feedback loops to generate a bistable switch at the level of E2F activation.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] This occurs due to three main interactions during late G1 phase.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] The first is a result of mitogen stimulation through the ERK leading to the expression of the transcription factor Myc, which is a direct activator of E2F.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] The second pathway is a result of ERK activation leading to the accumulation of active complexes of Cyclin D and Cdk4/6 which destabilize Rb via phosphorylation and further serve to activate E2F and promote expression of its targets.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] Finally, these interactions are all reinforced by an additional positive feedback loop by E2F on itself, as its own expression leads to production of the active complex of Cyclin E and CDK2, which further serves to lock in a cell's decision to enter S-phase.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] As a result, when serum concentration is increased in a gradual manner, most mammalian cells respond in a switch-like manner in entering S-phase.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] This mitogen-stimulated, bistable E2F switch exhibits hysteresis, as cells are inhibited from returning to G1 even after mitogen withdrawal post-E2F activation.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] They measured signal strength and dynamics with steady-state EGF stimulation, in which the signaling and output can be easily related.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] They further mapped the signal-response relationship across the pathway’s full dynamic range.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] Using high-content immunofluorescence (HCIF) detection of phosphorylated ERK (pERK) and live cell FRET biosensors, they monitored downstream output of the ERK pathway in both live cells and fixed cells.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] To further link the quantitative characteristics of ERK signaling to proliferation rates, they established a series of steady-state conditions using a range of EGF concentrations by applying EGF with different concentrations.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] Single cell imaging experiments have shown ERK to be activated in stochastic bursts in the presence of EGF.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] Furthermore, the pathway has been shown to encode the strength of signaling inputs though frequency modulated pulses of its activity.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] Using live cell FRET biosensors, cells induced with different concentrations of EGF illicit activity bursts of different frequency, where higher levels of EGF resulted in more frequent bursts of ERK activity.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] They found that longer periods of ERK activity stimulate S phase entry, as suggested by increased pulse length.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] To understand the dynamics of EGFR-ERK pathway, specifically how is the frequency and amplitude modulated, they applied the EGFR inhibitor gefitinib or the highly selective MAPK/ERK kinase (MEK) inhibitor PD0325901 (PD).
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] Two inhibitors yield actually a little bit different result: gefitinib, at intermediate concentration, would induce pulsatory behavior and also bimodal shift, which is not observed with PD.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] They further combine EGF and PD together and draw the conclusion that the frequency of ERK activities is modulated by quantitative variation while the amplitude is modulated by MEK activity’s change.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] Lastly they turned to Fra-1, one of downstream effectors of ERK pathway, as it’s technically challenging to estimate ERK activities directly.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] The fluctuation of ERK signaling highlights potential issues with current therapeutic approaches, providing new perspective in terms of thinking about drug targeting in the ERK pathway in cancer.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] Rather than daughter cells starting with no key signaling proteins after division, mitogen/ERK induced Cyclin D1 mRNA and DNA damage induced p53 protein, both long lived factors in cells, can be stably inherited from mother cells after cell division.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] The levels of these regulators vary from cell to cell after mitosis and stoichiometry between them strongly influences cell cycle commitment though activation of Cdk2.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] These results illustrate a form of encoded molecular memory though the history of mitogen signaling through ERK and stress response though p53.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] Uncontrolled growth is a necessary step for the development of all cancers.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] In many cancers (e.g. melanoma), a defect in the MAP/ERK pathway leads to that uncontrolled growth.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] Many compounds can inhibit steps in the MAP/ERK pathway, and therefore are potential drugs for treating cancer, such as Hodgkin disease.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] The first drug licensed to act on this pathway is sorafenib — a Raf kinase inhibitor.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] Other Raf inhibitors include SB590885, PLX4720, XL281, RAF265, encorafenib, dabrafenib, and vemurafenib.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] It has been found that acupoint-moxibustion has a role in relieving alcohol-induced gastric mucosal injury in a mouse model, which may be closely associated with its effects in up-regulating activities of the epidermal growth factor/ERK signal transduction pathway.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] RAF-ERK pathway is also involved in the pathophysiology of Noonan syndrome, a polymalformative disease.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] Protein microarray analysis can be used to detect subtle changes in protein activity in signaling pathways.
[src:signal-transduction/mapk-erk-pathway] The developmental syndromes caused by germline mutations in genes that alter the RAS components of the MAP/ERK signal transduction pathway are called RASopathies.
[src:signal-transduction/protein-kinase] A **protein kinase** is a kinase which selectively modifies other proteins by covalently adding phosphates to them (phosphorylation) as opposed to kinases which modify lipids, carbohydrates, or other molecules.
[src:signal-transduction/protein-kinase] Phosphorylation usually results in a functional change of the target protein (substrate) by changing enzyme activity, cellular location, or association with other proteins.
[src:signal-transduction/protein-kinase] The human genome contains about 500 protein kinase genes and they constitute about 2% of all human genes.
[src:signal-transduction/protein-kinase] There are two main types of protein kinase.
[src:signal-transduction/protein-kinase] The great majority are serine/threonine kinases, which phosphorylate the hydroxyl groups of serines and threonines in their targets.
[src:signal-transduction/protein-kinase] Most of the others are tyrosine kinases, although additional types exist.
[src:signal-transduction/protein-kinase] Protein kinases are also found in bacteria and plants.
[src:signal-transduction/protein-kinase] Up to 30% of all human proteins may be modified by kinase activity, and kinases are known to regulate the majority of cellular pathways, especially those involved in signal transduction.
[src:signal-transduction/protein-kinase] The chemical activity of a protein kinase involves removing a phosphate group from ATP and covalently attaching it to one of three amino acids that have a free hydroxyl group.
[src:signal-transduction/protein-kinase] Most kinases act on both serine and threonine, others act on tyrosine, and a number (dual-specificity kinases) act on all three.
[src:signal-transduction/protein-kinase] There are also protein kinases that phosphorylate other amino acids, including histidine kinases that phosphorylate histidine residues.
[src:signal-transduction/protein-kinase] Eukaryotic protein kinases are enzymes that belong to a very extensive family of proteins that share a conserved catalytic core.
[src:signal-transduction/protein-kinase] The structures of over 280 human protein kinases have been determined.
[src:signal-transduction/protein-kinase] There are a number of conserved regions in the catalytic domain of protein kinases.
[src:signal-transduction/protein-kinase] In the N-terminal extremity of the catalytic domain there is a glycine-rich stretch of residues in the vicinity of a lysine amino acid, which has been shown to be involved in ATP binding.
[src:signal-transduction/protein-kinase] In the central part of the catalytic domain, there is a conserved aspartic acid, which is important for the catalytic activity of the enzyme.
[src:signal-transduction/protein-kinase] Serine/threonine protein kinases (EC 2.7.11.-) phosphorylate the OH group of serine or threonine (which have similar side chains).
[src:signal-transduction/protein-kinase] Activity of these protein kinases can be regulated by specific events (e.g., DNA damage), as well as numerous chemical signals, including cAMP/cGMP, diacylglycerol, and Ca2+/calmodulin.
[src:signal-transduction/protein-kinase] One very important group of protein kinases are the MAP kinases (acronym from: "mitogen-activated protein kinases").
[src:signal-transduction/protein-kinase] Important subgroups are the kinases of the ERK subfamily, typically activated by mitogenic signals, and the stress-activated protein kinases JNK and p38.
[src:signal-transduction/protein-kinase] While MAP kinases are serine/threonine-specific, they are activated by combined phosphorylation on serine/threonine and tyrosine residues.
[src:signal-transduction/protein-kinase] Activity of MAP kinases is restricted by a number of protein phosphatases, which remove the phosphate groups that are added to specific serine or threonine residues of the kinase and are required to maintain the kinase in an active conformation.
[src:signal-transduction/protein-kinase] Tyrosine-specific protein kinases (EC 2.7.10.-) phosphorylate tyrosine amino acid residues, and like serine/threonine-specific kinases are used in signal transduction.
[src:signal-transduction/protein-kinase] They act primarily as growth factor receptors and in downstream signaling from growth factors.
[src:signal-transduction/protein-kinase] These kinases consist of extracellular domains, a transmembrane spanning alpha helix, and an intracellular tyrosine kinase domain protruding into the cytoplasm.
[src:signal-transduction/protein-kinase] They play important roles in regulating cell division, cellular differentiation, and morphogenesis.
[src:signal-transduction/protein-kinase] More than 50 receptor tyrosine kinases are known in mammals.
[src:signal-transduction/protein-kinase] The extracellular domains serve as the ligand-binding part of the molecule, often inducing the domains to form homo- or heterodimers.
[src:signal-transduction/protein-kinase] The transmembrane element is a single α helix.
[src:signal-transduction/protein-kinase] The intracellular or cytoplasmic Protein kinase domain is responsible for the (highly conserved) kinase activity, as well as several regulatory functions.
[src:signal-transduction/protein-kinase] *Trans*-autophosphorylation (phosphorylation by the other kinase in the dimer) of the kinase.
[src:signal-transduction/protein-kinase] Autophosphorylation stabilizes the active conformation of the kinase domain.
[src:signal-transduction/protein-kinase] The active tyrosine kinase phosphorylates specific target proteins, which are often enzymes themselves.
[src:signal-transduction/protein-kinase] An important target is the ras protein signal-transduction chain.
[src:signal-transduction/protein-kinase] Tyrosine kinases recruited to a receptor following hormone binding are receptor-associated tyrosine kinases and are involved in a number of signaling cascades, in particular those involved in cytokine signaling (but also others, including growth hormone).
[src:signal-transduction/protein-kinase] One such receptor-associated tyrosine kinase is Janus kinase (JAK), many of whose effects are mediated by STAT proteins.
[src:signal-transduction/protein-kinase] Some kinases have dual-specificity kinase (EC 2.7.12.-) activities.
[src:signal-transduction/protein-kinase] For example, MEK (MAPKK), which is involved in the MAP kinase cascade, is a both a serine/threonine and tyrosine kinase.
[src:signal-transduction/protein-kinase] Protein kinases are enzymes that regulate cellular processes by catalyzing the phosphorylation of specific substrates, thereby modulating signaling pathways involved in growth, differentiation, metabolism, and survival.
[src:signal-transduction/protein-kinase] Among these, the RAF family of serine/threonine protein kinases plays a central role in the MAPK/ERK signaling cascade.
[src:signal-transduction/protein-kinase] During his postdoctoral research at Novartis Pharmaceuticals, Anton Yuryev contributed to studies examining the subcellular localization and functional diversity of protein kinases, demonstrating that the mammalian A-RAF kinase can be imported into mitochondria.
[src:signal-transduction/protein-kinase] This observation provided evidence that protein kinases may function outside their traditional cytosolic and membrane-associated signaling contexts, extending their regulatory influence to mitochondrial processes.
[src:signal-transduction/protein-kinase] Such findings highlighted the broader role of protein kinase compartmentalization in coordinating intracellular signaling with organelle-specific functions.
[src:signal-transduction/protein-kinase] Histidine kinases (EC 2.7.13.-) are structurally distinct from most other protein kinases and are found mostly in prokaryotes as part of two-component signal transduction mechanisms.
[src:signal-transduction/protein-kinase] A phosphate group from ATP is first added to a histidine residue within the kinase, and later transferred to an aspartate residue on a 'receiver domain' on a different protein, or sometimes on the kinase itself.
[src:signal-transduction/protein-kinase] The aspartyl phosphate residue is then active in signaling.
[src:signal-transduction/protein-kinase] Histidine kinases are found widely in prokaryotes, as well as in plants, fungi and eukaryotes.
[src:signal-transduction/protein-kinase] The pyruvate dehydrogenase family of kinases in animals is structurally related to histidine kinases, but instead phosphorylate serine residues, and probably do not use a phospho-histidine intermediate.
[src:signal-transduction/protein-kinase] Deregulated kinase activity is a frequent cause of disease, in particular cancer, wherein kinases regulate many aspects that control cell growth, movement and death.
[src:signal-transduction/protein-kinase] Drugs that inhibit specific kinases are being developed to treat several diseases, and some are currently in clinical use, including Gleevec (imatinib) and Iressa (gefitinib).
[src:signal-transduction/protein-kinase] Drug developments for kinase inhibitors are started from kinase assays Archived 2014-11-26 at the Wayback Machine, the lead compounds are usually profiled for specificity before moving into further tests.
[src:signal-transduction/protein-kinase] Many profiling services are available from fluorescent-based assays to radioisotope based detections, and competition binding assays.
[src:signal-transduction/second-messenger-system] They are one of the triggers of intracellular signal transduction cascades.
[src:signal-transduction/second-messenger-system] Examples of second messenger molecules include cyclic AMP, cyclic GMP, inositol triphosphate, diacylglycerol, and calcium.
[src:signal-transduction/second-messenger-system] First messengers are extracellular factors, often hormones or neurotransmitters, such as epinephrine, growth hormone, and serotonin.
[src:signal-transduction/second-messenger-system] Because peptide hormones and neurotransmitters typically are biochemically hydrophilic molecules, these first messengers may not physically cross the phospholipid bilayer to initiate changes within the cell directly—unlike steroid hormones, which usually do.
[src:signal-transduction/second-messenger-system] This functional limitation requires the cell to have signal transduction mechanisms to transduce first messenger into second messengers, so that the extracellular signal may be propagated intracellularly.
[src:signal-transduction/second-messenger-system] An important feature of the second messenger signaling system is that second messengers may be coupled downstream to multi-cyclic kinase cascades to greatly amplify the strength of the original first messenger signal.
[src:signal-transduction/second-messenger-system] For example, RasGTP signals link with the mitogen activated protein kinase (MAPK) cascade to amplify the allosteric activation of proliferative transcription factors such as Myc and CREB.
[src:signal-transduction/second-messenger-system] Earl Wilbur Sutherland Jr., discovered second messengers, for which he won the 1971 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine.
[src:signal-transduction/second-messenger-system] Sutherland saw that epinephrine would stimulate the liver to convert glycogen to glucose (sugar) in liver cells, but epinephrine alone would not convert glycogen to glucose.
[src:signal-transduction/second-messenger-system] He found that epinephrine had to trigger a second messenger, cyclic AMP, for the liver to convert glycogen to glucose.
[src:signal-transduction/second-messenger-system] The mechanisms were worked out in detail by Martin Rodbell and Alfred G.
[src:signal-transduction/second-messenger-system] Secondary messenger systems can be synthesized and activated by enzymes, for example, the cyclases that synthesize cyclic nucleotides, or by opening of ion channels to allow influx of metal ions, for example Ca2+ signaling.
[src:signal-transduction/second-messenger-system] These small molecules bind and activate protein kinases, ion channels, and other proteins, thus continuing the signaling cascade.
[src:signal-transduction/second-messenger-system] There are several different secondary messenger systems (cAMP system, phosphoinositol system, and arachidonic acid system), but they all are quite similar in overall mechanism, although the substances involved and overall effects can vary.
[src:signal-transduction/second-messenger-system] In most cases, a ligand binds to a cell surface receptor.
[src:signal-transduction/second-messenger-system] The binding of a ligand to the receptor causes a conformation change in the receptor.
[src:signal-transduction/second-messenger-system] This conformation change can affect the activity of the receptor and result in the production of active second messengers.
[src:signal-transduction/second-messenger-system] In the case of G protein-coupled receptors, the conformation change exposes a binding site for a *G-protein*.
[src:signal-transduction/second-messenger-system] The G-protein (named for the GDP and GTP molecules that bind to it) is bound to the inner membrane of the cell and consists of three subunits: alpha, beta and gamma.
[src:signal-transduction/second-messenger-system] When the G-protein binds with the receptor, it becomes able to exchange a GDP (guanosine diphosphate) molecule on its alpha subunit for a GTP (guanosine triphosphate) molecule.
[src:signal-transduction/second-messenger-system] Once this exchange takes place, the alpha subunit of the G-protein transducer breaks free from the beta and gamma subunits, all parts remaining membrane-bound.
[src:signal-transduction/second-messenger-system] The primary effector then has an action, which creates a signal that can diffuse within the cell.
[src:signal-transduction/second-messenger-system] This signal is called the "second (or secondary) messenger." The secondary messenger may then activate a "secondary effector" whose effects depend on the particular secondary messenger system.
[src:signal-transduction/second-messenger-system] Calcium ions are one type of second messengers and are responsible for many important physiological functions including muscle contraction, fertilization, and neurotransmitter release.
[src:signal-transduction/second-messenger-system] The ions are normally bound or stored in intracellular components (such as the endoplasmic reticulum(ER)) and can be released during signal transduction.
[src:signal-transduction/second-messenger-system] The enzyme phospholipase C produces diacylglycerol and inositol trisphosphate, which increases calcium ion permeability into the membrane.
[src:signal-transduction/second-messenger-system] Active G-protein open up calcium channels to let calcium ions enter the plasma membrane.
[src:signal-transduction/second-messenger-system] The other product of phospholipase C, diacylglycerol, activates protein kinase C, which assists in the activation of cAMP (another second messenger).
[src:signal-transduction/second-messenger-system] IP3, DAG, and Ca2+ are second messengers in the phosphoinositol pathway.
[src:signal-transduction/second-messenger-system] The pathway begins with the binding of extracellular primary messengers such as epinephrine, acetylcholine, and hormones AGT, GnRH, GHRH, oxytocin, and TRH, to their respective receptors.
[src:signal-transduction/second-messenger-system] Epinephrine binds to the α1 GTPase Protein Coupled Receptor (GPCR) and acetylcholine binds to M1 and M2 GPCR.
[src:signal-transduction/second-messenger-system] Binding of a primary messenger to these receptors results in conformational change of the receptor.
[src:signal-transduction/second-messenger-system] The α subunit, with the help of guanine nucleotide exchange factors (GEFS), releases GDP, and binds GTP, resulting in the dissociation of the subunit and subsequent activation.
[src:signal-transduction/second-messenger-system] The activated α subunit activates phospholipase C, which hydrolyzes membrane bound phosphatidylinositol 4,5-bisphosphate (PIP2), resulting in the formation of secondary messengers diacylglycerol (DAG) and inositol-1,4,5-triphosphate (IP3).
[src:signal-transduction/second-messenger-system] IP3 binds to calcium pumps on ER, transporting Ca2+, another second messenger, into the cytoplasm.
[src:signal-transduction/second-messenger-system] Ca2+ ultimately binds to many proteins, activating a cascade of enzymatic pathways.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] When signaling pathways interact with one another they form networks, which allow cellular responses to be coordinated, often by combinatorial signaling events.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] At the molecular level, such responses include changes in the transcription or translation of genes, and post-translational and conformational changes in proteins, as well as changes in their location.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] These molecular events are the basic mechanisms controlling cell growth, proliferation, metabolism and many other processes.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] In multicellular organisms, signal transduction pathways regulate cell communication in a wide variety of ways.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Each component (or node) of a signaling pathway is classified according to the role it plays with respect to the initial stimulus.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Ligands are termed *first messengers*, while receptors are the *signal transducers*, which then activate *primary effectors*.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Such effectors are typically proteins and are often linked to second messengers, which can activate *secondary effectors*, and so on.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Depending on the efficiency of the nodes, a signal can be amplified (a concept known as signal gain), so that one signaling molecule can generate a response involving hundreds to millions of molecules.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] As with other signals, the transduction of biological signals is characterised by delay, noise, signal feedback and feedforward and interference, which can range from negligible to pathological.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] With the advent of computational biology, the analysis of signaling pathways and networks has become an essential tool to understand cellular functions and disease, including signaling rewiring mechanisms underlying responses to acquired drug resistance.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] The basis for signal transduction is the transformation of a certain stimulus into a biochemical signal.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] The nature of such stimuli can vary widely, ranging from extracellular cues, such as the presence of epidermal growth factor (EGF), to intracellular events, such as the DNA damage resulting from replicative telomere attrition.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Traditionally, signals that reach the central nervous system are classified as senses.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] These are transmitted from neuron to neuron in a process called synaptic transmission.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Many other intercellular signal relay mechanisms exist in multicellular organisms, such as those that govern embryonic development.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] The majority of signal transduction pathways involve the binding of signaling molecules, known as ligands, to receptors that trigger events inside the cell.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] The binding of a signaling molecule with a receptor causes a change in the conformation of the receptor, known as *receptor activation*.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Most ligands are soluble molecules from the extracellular medium which bind to cell surface receptors.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] These include growth factors, cytokines and neurotransmitters.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Components of the extracellular matrix such as fibronectin and hyaluronan can also bind to such receptors (integrins and CD44, respectively).
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] In addition, some molecules such as steroid hormones are lipid-soluble and thus cross the plasma membrane to reach cytoplasmic or nuclear receptors.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] In the case of steroid hormone receptors, their stimulation leads to binding to the promoter region of steroid-responsive genes.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Not all classifications of signaling molecules take into account the molecular nature of each class member.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] For example, odorants belong to a wide range of molecular classes, as do neurotransmitters, which range in size from small molecules such as dopamine to neuropeptides such as endorphins.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Moreover, some molecules may fit into more than one class, e.g. epinephrine is a neurotransmitter when secreted by the central nervous system and a hormone when secreted by the adrenal medulla.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Some receptors such as HER2 are capable of ligand-independent activation when overexpressed or mutated.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] This leads to constitutive activation of the pathway, which may or may not be overturned by compensation mechanisms.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] In the case of HER2, which acts as a dimerization partner of other epidermal growth factor receptors (EGFR), constitutive activation leads to hyperproliferation and cancer.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] The prevalence of basement membranes in the tissues of eumetazoans means that most cell types require attachment to survive.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] This requirement has led to the development of complex mechanotransduction pathways, allowing cells to sense the stiffness of the substratum.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Such signaling is mainly orchestrated in focal adhesions, regions where the integrin-bound actin cytoskeleton detects changes and transmits them downstream through YAP1.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Calcium-dependent cell adhesion molecules such as cadherins and selectins can also mediate mechanotransduction.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Specialised forms of mechanotransduction within the nervous system are responsible for mechanosensation: hearing, touch, proprioception and balance.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Cellular and systemic control of osmotic pressure (the difference in osmolarity between the cytosol and the extracellular medium) is critical for homeostasis.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] There are three ways in which cells can detect osmotic stimuli: as changes in macromolecular crowding, ionic strength, and changes in the properties of the plasma membrane or cytoskeleton (the latter being a form of mechanotransduction).
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] These changes are detected by proteins known as osmosensors or osmoreceptors.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] In humans, the best characterised osmosensors are transient receptor potential channels present in the primary cilium of human cells.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] In yeast, the HOG pathway has been extensively characterised.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] The sensing of temperature in cells is known as thermoception and is primarily mediated by transient receptor potential channels.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Additionally, animal cells contain a conserved mechanism to prevent high temperatures from causing cellular damage, the heat-shock response.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Such response is triggered when high temperatures cause the dissociation of inactive HSF1 from complexes with heat shock proteins Hsp40/Hsp70 and Hsp90.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] With help from the ncRNA *hsr1*, HSF1 then trimerizes, becoming active and upregulating the expression of its target genes.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Many other thermosensory mechanisms exist in both prokaryotes and eukaryotes.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] In mammals, light controls the sense of sight and the circadian clock by activating light-sensitive proteins in photoreceptor cells in the eye's retina.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] In the case of vision, light is detected by rhodopsin in rod and cone cells.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] In the case of the circadian clock, a different photopigment, melanopsin, is responsible for detecting light in intrinsically photosensitive retinal ganglion cells.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Receptors can be roughly divided into two major classes: intracellular and extracellular receptors.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Extracellular receptors are integral transmembrane proteins and make up most receptors.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] They span the plasma membrane of the cell, with one part of the receptor on the outside and the other on the inside.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Signal transduction occurs as a result of a ligand binding to the outside region of the receptor (the ligand does not pass through the membrane).
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Ligand-receptor binding induces a change in the conformation of the inside part of the receptor, a process sometimes called "receptor activation".
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] This results in either the activation of an enzyme domain of the receptor or the exposure of a binding site for other intracellular signaling proteins within the cell, eventually propagating the signal through the cytoplasm.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] In eukaryotic cells, most intracellular proteins activated by a ligand/receptor interaction possess an enzymatic activity; examples include tyrosine kinase and phosphatases.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Often, such enzymes are covalently linked to the receptor.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Some of them create second messengers such as cyclic AMP and IP3, the latter controlling the release of intracellular calcium stores into the cytoplasm.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Other activated proteins interact with adaptor proteins that facilitate signaling protein interactions and coordination of signaling complexes necessary to respond to a particular stimulus.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Enzymes and adaptor proteins are both responsive to various second messenger molecules.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Many adaptor proteins and enzymes activated as part of signal transduction possess specialized protein domains that bind to specific secondary messenger molecules.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] For example, calcium ions bind to the EF hand domains of calmodulin, allowing it to bind and activate calmodulin-dependent kinase.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] PIP3 and other phosphoinositides do the same thing to the Pleckstrin homology domains of proteins such as the kinase protein AKT.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] G protein–coupled receptors (GPCRs) are a family of integral transmembrane proteins that possess seven transmembrane domains and are linked to a heterotrimeric G protein.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] With nearly 800 members, this is the largest family of membrane proteins and receptors in mammals.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Counting all animal species, they total over 5000.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Mammalian GPCRs are classified into five major families: rhodopsin-like, secretin-like, metabotropic glutamate, adhesion and frizzled/smoothened, with a few GPCR groups being difficult to classify due to low sequence similarity, e.g. vomeronasal receptors.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Other classes exist in eukaryotes, such as the *Dictyostelium* cyclic AMP receptors and fungal mating pheromone receptors.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Signal transduction by a GPCR begins with an inactive G protein coupled to the receptor; the G protein exists as a heterotrimer consisting of Gα, Gβ, and Gγ subunits.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Once the GPCR recognizes a ligand, the conformation of the receptor changes to activate the G protein, causing Gα to bind a molecule of GTP and dissociate from the other two G-protein subunits.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] The dissociation exposes sites on the subunits that can interact with other molecules.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] The activated G protein subunits detach from the receptor and initiate signaling from many downstream effector proteins such as phospholipases and ion channels, the latter permitting the release of second messenger molecules.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] A study was conducted where a point mutation was inserted into the gene encoding the chemokine receptor CXCR2; mutated cells underwent a malignant transformation due to the expression of CXCR2 in an active conformation despite the absence of chemokine-binding.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] This meant that chemokine receptors can contribute to cancer development.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Receptor tyrosine kinases (RTKs) are transmembrane proteins with an intracellular kinase domain and an extracellular domain that binds ligands; examples include growth factor receptors such as the insulin receptor.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] To perform signal transduction, RTKs need to form dimers in the plasma membrane; the dimer is stabilized by ligands binding to the receptor.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] The interaction between the cytoplasmic domains stimulates the autophosphorylation of tyrosine residues within the intracellular kinase domains of the RTKs, causing conformational changes.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Subsequent to this, the receptors' kinase domains are activated, initiating phosphorylation signaling cascades of downstream cytoplasmic molecules that facilitate various cellular processes such as cell differentiation and metabolism.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Many Ser/Thr and dual-specificity protein kinases are important for signal transduction, either acting downstream of [receptor tyrosine kinases], or as membrane-embedded or cell-soluble versions in their own right.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] As is the case with GPCRs, proteins that bind GTP play a major role in signal transduction from the activated RTK into the cell.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] In this case, the G proteins are members of the Ras, Rho, and Raf families, referred to collectively as small G proteins.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] They act as molecular switches usually tethered to membranes by isoprenyl groups linked to their carboxyl ends.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Upon activation, they assign proteins to specific membrane subdomains where they participate in signaling.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Activated RTKs in turn activate small G proteins that activate guanine nucleotide exchange factors such as SOS1.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Once activated, these exchange factors can activate more small G proteins, thus amplifying the receptor's initial signal.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] The mutation of certain RTK genes, as with that of GPCRs, can result in the expression of receptors that exist in a constitutively activated state; such mutated genes may act as oncogenes.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Integrins are produced by a wide variety of cells; they play a role in cell attachment to other cells and the extracellular matrix and in the transduction of signals from extracellular matrix components such as fibronectin and collagen.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Ligand binding to the extracellular domain of integrins changes the protein's conformation, clustering it at the cell membrane to initiate signal transduction.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Integrins lack kinase activity; hence, integrin-mediated signal transduction is achieved through a variety of intracellular protein kinases and adaptor molecules, the main coordinator being integrin-linked kinase.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] As shown in the adjacent picture, cooperative integrin-RTK signaling determines the timing of cellular survival, apoptosis, proliferation, and differentiation.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Important differences exist between integrin-signaling in circulating blood cells and non-circulating cells such as epithelial cells; integrins of circulating cells are normally inactive.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] For example, cell membrane integrins on circulating leukocytes are maintained in an inactive state to avoid epithelial cell attachment; they are activated only in response to stimuli such as those received at the site of an inflammatory response.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] In a similar manner, integrins at the cell membrane of circulating platelets are normally kept inactive to avoid thrombosis.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Epithelial cells (which are non-circulating) normally have active integrins at their cell membrane, helping maintain their stable adhesion to underlying stromal cells that provide signals to maintain normal functioning.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] In plants, there are no bona fide integrin receptors identified to date; nevertheless, several integrin-like proteins were proposed based on structural homology with the metazoan receptors.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Plants contain integrin-linked kinases that are very similar in their primary structure with the animal ILKs.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] In the experimental model plant *Arabidopsis thaliana*, one of the integrin-linked kinase genes, *ILK1*, has been shown to be a critical element in the plant immune response to signal molecules from bacterial pathogens and plant sensitivity to salt and osmotic stress.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] ILK1 protein interacts with the high-affinity potassium transporter HAK5 and with the calcium sensor CML9.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] When activated, toll-like receptors (TLRs) take adapter molecules within the cytoplasm of cells in order to propagate a signal.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Five adaptor molecules are known to be involved in signaling, which are Myd88, TIRAP, TRIF, TRAM, and SARM1.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] These adapters activate other intracellular molecules such as IRAK1, IRAK4, TBK1, and IKKi that amplify the signal, eventually leading to the induction or suppression of genes that cause certain responses.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Thousands of genes are activated by TLR signaling, implying that this method constitutes an important gateway for gene modulation.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] A ligand-gated ion channel, upon binding with a ligand, changes conformation to open a channel in the cell membrane through which ions relaying signals can pass.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] An example of this mechanism is found in the receiving cell of a neural synapse.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] The influx of ions that occurs in response to the opening of these channels induces action potentials, such as those that travel along nerves, by depolarizing the membrane of post-synaptic cells, resulting in the opening of voltage-gated ion channels.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] An example of an ion allowed into the cell during a ligand-gated ion channel opening is Ca2+; it acts as a second messenger initiating signal transduction cascades and altering the physiology of the responding cell.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] This results in amplification of the synapse response between synaptic cells by remodelling the dendritic spines involved in the synapse.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Intracellular receptors, such as nuclear receptors and cytoplasmic receptors, are soluble proteins localized within their respective areas.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] The typical ligands for nuclear receptors are non-polar hormones like the steroid hormones testosterone and progesterone and derivatives of vitamins A and D.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] To initiate signal transduction, the ligand must pass through the plasma membrane by passive diffusion.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] On binding with the receptor, the ligands pass through the nuclear membrane into the nucleus, altering gene expression.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Activated nuclear receptors attach to the DNA at receptor-specific hormone-responsive element (HRE) sequences, located in the promoter region of the genes activated by the hormone-receptor complex.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Due to their enabling gene transcription, they are alternatively called inductors of gene expression.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Nucleic receptors have DNA-binding domains containing zinc fingers and a ligand-binding domain; the zinc fingers stabilize DNA binding by holding its phosphate backbone.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] DNA sequences that match the receptor are usually hexameric repeats of any kind; the sequences are similar but their orientation and distance differentiate them.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] The ligand-binding domain is additionally responsible for dimerization of nucleic receptors prior to binding and providing structures for transactivation used for communication with the translational apparatus.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Steroid receptors are a subclass of nuclear receptors located primarily within the cytosol.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] In the absence of steroids, they associate in an aporeceptor complex containing chaperone or heatshock proteins (HSPs).
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] The HSPs are necessary to activate the receptor by assisting the protein to fold in a way such that the signal sequence enabling its passage into the nucleus is accessible.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Steroid receptors, on the other hand, may be repressive on gene expression when their transactivation domain is hidden.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Receptor activity can be enhanced by phosphorylation of serine residues at their N-terminal as a result of another signal transduction pathway, a process called crosstalk.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Retinoic acid receptors are another subset of nuclear receptors.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] They can be activated by an endocrine-synthesized ligand that entered the cell by diffusion, a ligand synthesised from a precursor like retinol brought to the cell through the bloodstream or a completely intracellularly synthesised ligand like prostaglandin.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] These receptors are located in the nucleus and are not accompanied by HSPs.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] They repress their gene by binding to their specific DNA sequence when no ligand binds to them, and vice versa.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Certain intracellular receptors of the immune system are cytoplasmic receptors; recently identified NOD-like receptors (NLRs) reside in the cytoplasm of some eukaryotic cells and interact with ligands using a leucine-rich repeat (LRR) motif similar to TLRs.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Some of these molecules like NOD2 interact with RIP2 kinase that activates NF-κB signaling, whereas others like NALP3 interact with inflammatory caspases and initiate processing of particular cytokines like interleukin-1β.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] First messengers are the signaling molecules (hormones, neurotransmitters, and paracrine/autocrine agents) that reach the cell from the extracellular fluid and bind to their specific receptors.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Second messengers are the substances that enter the cytoplasm and act within the cell to trigger a response.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] In essence, second messengers act as chemical relays from the plasma membrane to the cytoplasm, thus carrying out intracellular signal transduction.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] The release of calcium ions from the endoplasmic reticulum into the cytosol results in its binding to signaling proteins that are then activated; it is then sequestered in the smooth endoplasmic reticulum and the mitochondria.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Calcium is involved in numerous cellular processes, including muscle contraction, neurotransmitter release from nerve endings, and cell migration.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Its activation is primarily mediated through three main pathways: G-protein–coupled receptor (GPCR) pathways, receptor tyrosine kinase (RTK) pathways, and gated ion channels.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Calcium regulates proteins either directly or indirectly by binding to enzymes such as calmodulin-dependent kinases.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Lipophilic second messenger molecules are derived from lipids residing in cellular membranes; enzymes stimulated by activated receptors activate the lipids by modifying them.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Examples include diacylglycerol and ceramide, the former required for the activation of protein kinase C.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Nitric oxide (NO) acts as a second messenger because it is a free radical that can diffuse through the plasma membrane and affect nearby cells.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] It is synthesised from arginine and oxygen by the NO synthase and works through activation of soluble guanylyl cyclase, which, when activated, produces another second messenger, cGMP.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] NO can also act through covalent modification of proteins or their metal cofactors; some have a redox mechanism and are reversible.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] It is toxic in high concentrations and causes damage during stroke, but is the cause of many other functions like the relaxation of blood vessels, apoptosis, and penile erections.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] In addition to nitric oxide, other electronically activated species are also signal-transducing agents in a process called redox signaling.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Examples include superoxide, hydrogen peroxide, carbon monoxide, and hydrogen sulfide.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Redox signaling also includes active modulation of electronic flows in semiconductive biological macromolecules.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Gene activations and metabolism alterations are examples of cellular responses to extracellular stimulation that require signal transduction.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Gene activation leads to further cellular effects, since the products of responding genes include instigators of activation; transcription factors produced as a result of a signal transduction cascade can activate even more genes.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Hence, an initial stimulus can trigger the expression of a large number of genes, leading to physiological events like the increased uptake of glucose from the blood stream and the migration of neutrophils to sites of infection.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] The set of genes and their activation order to certain stimuli is referred to as a genetic program.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Mammalian cells require stimulation for cell division and survival; in the absence of growth factor, apoptosis ensues.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Such requirements for extracellular stimulation are necessary for controlling cell behavior in unicellular and multicellular organisms; signal transduction pathways are perceived to be so central to biological processes that a large number of diseases are attributed to their dysregulation.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] The combination of these signals is integrated into altered cytoplasmic machinery which leads to altered cell behaviour.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Following are some major signaling pathways, demonstrating how ligands binding to their receptors can affect second messengers and eventually result in altered cellular responses.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] The earliest notion of signal transduction can be traced back to 1855, when Claude Bernard proposed that ductless glands such as the spleen, the thyroid and adrenal glands, were responsible for the release of "internal secretions" with physiological effects.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Bernard's "secretions" were later named "hormones" by Ernest Starling in 1905.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Together with William Bayliss, Starling had discovered secretin in 1902.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Although many other hormones, most notably insulin, were discovered in the following years, the mechanisms remained largely unknown.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] The discovery of nerve growth factor by Rita Levi-Montalcini in 1954, and epidermal growth factor by Stanley Cohen in 1962, led to more detailed insights into the molecular basis of cell signaling, in particular growth factors.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Their work, together with Earl Wilbur Sutherland's discovery of cyclic AMP in 1956, prompted the redefinition of endocrine signaling to include only signaling from glands, while the terms autocrine and paracrine began to be used.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Sutherland was awarded the 1971 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine, while Levi-Montalcini and Cohen shared it in 1986.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] In 1970, Martin Rodbell examined the effects of glucagon on a rat's liver cell membrane receptor.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] He noted that guanosine triphosphate disassociated glucagon from this receptor and stimulated the G-protein, which strongly influenced the cell's metabolism.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Thus, he deduced that the G-protein is a transducer that accepts glucagon molecules and affects the cell.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] For this, he shared the 1994 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine with Alfred G.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Thus, the characterization of RTKs and GPCRs led to the formulation of the concept of "signal transduction", a word first used in 1972.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Some early articles used the terms *signal transmission* and *sensory transduction*.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] In 2007, a total of 48,377 scientific papers—including 11,211 review papers—were published on the subject.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] The term first appeared in a paper's title in 1979.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Widespread use of the term has been traced to a 1980 review article by Rodbell: Research papers focusing on signal transduction first appeared in large numbers in the late 1980s and early 1990s.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] The purpose of this section is to briefly describe some developments in immunology in the 1960s and 1970s, relevant to the initial stages of transmembrane signal transduction, and how they impacted our understanding of immunology, and ultimately of other areas of cell biology.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] The relevant events begin with the sequencing of myeloma protein light chains, which are found in abundance in the urine of individuals with multiple myeloma.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Biochemical experiments revealed that these so-called Bence Jones proteins consisted of 2 discrete domains –one that varied from one molecule to the next (the V domain) and one that did not (the Fc domain or the Fragment crystallizable region).
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] An analysis of multiple V region sequences by Wu and Kabat identified locations within the V region that were hypervariable and which, they hypothesized, combined in the folded protein to form the antigen recognition site.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Thus, within a relatively short time a plausible model was developed for the molecular basis of immunological specificity, and for mediation of biological function through the Fc domain.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Crystallization of an IgG molecule soon followed ) confirming the inferences based on sequencing, and providing an understanding of immunological specificity at the highest level of resolution.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] The final piece of the story, the Fluid mosaic model of the plasma membrane provided all the ingredients for a new model for the initiation of signal transduction; viz, receptor dimerization.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] The latter observation was consistent with earlier findings by Fanger et al.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] These observations tied a biological response to events and structural details of molecules on the cell surface.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] A preponderance of evidence soon developed that receptor dimerization initiates responses (reviewed in ) in a variety of cell types, including B cells.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Such observations led to a number of theoretical (mathematical) developments.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] The first of these was a simple model proposed by Bell which resolved an apparent paradox: clustering forms stable networks; i.e. binding is essentially irreversible, whereas the affinities of antibodies secreted by B cells increase as the immune response progresses.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] A theory of the dynamics of cell surface clustering on lymphocyte membranes was developed by DeLisi and Perelson who found the size distribution of clusters as a function of time, and its dependence on the affinity and valence of the ligand.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Subsequent theories for basophils and mast cells were developed by Goldstein and Sobotka and their collaborators, all aimed at the analysis of dose-response patterns of immune cells and their biological correlates.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] For a recent review of clustering in immunological systems see.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] Ligand binding to cell surface receptors is also critical to motility, a phenomenon that is best understood in single-celled organisms.
[src:signal-transduction/signal-transduction] An example is a detection and response to concentration gradients by bacteria -–the classic mathematical theory appearing in.
